{"segment_id": "00022", "page_num": 22, "segment": "in approaching difficult topics in their conversations, which will help you\nlearn from your conversations and prepare for what comes next.\n\nIn Part II, Chapters 3 through 7, we’ve distilled our experience,\nlearnings, and mistakes into an “instruction manual” for the Five\nConversations: crucial discussions of the ve key characteristics that all\nhigh-performing teams share---not just software teams but all human\nteams.\n\ne Five Conversations are:\n\n1. e Trust Conversation: We hold a belief that those we work with,\n\ninside and outside the team, share our goals and values.\n\n2. e Fear Conversation: We openly discuss problems in our team\n\nand its environment and courageously attack those obstacles.\n\n3. e Why Conversation: We share a common, explicit purpose that\n\ninspires us.\n\n4. e Commitment Conversation: We regularly and reliably\n\nannounce what we will do and when.\n\n5. e Accountability Conversation: We radiate our intent to all\ninterested parties and explain publicly how our results stack up\nagainst commitments.*\n\nese ve conversations address attributes that give teams everything\nthey need to exploit modern, people-centric practices to the hilt. With\nthem it is possible to achieve elite-level delivery speeds, fearlessly adjusting\non the y and committing to show real customers working software that\nsolves their problems. And these are exactly the characteristics missing\nfrom the teams we see too often today, where standups are places to hide\nprogress rather than share it, where estimation is a forlorn exercise in\nfutility, where the team’s purpose is lost in a sea of tickets, and where\nfrustration is the shared emotion from one end of the organization to the\nother.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "e Five Conversations are: e Fear Conversation: We openly discuss problems in our team e Why Conversation: We share a common, explicit purpose that", "l2_summary": "In Part II, Chapters 3 through 7, we’ve distilled our experience,\nlearnings, and mistakes into an “instruction manual” for the Five\nConversations: crucial discussions of the ve key characteristics that all\nhigh-performing teams share---not just software teams but all human\nteams. e Five Conversations are: e Trust Conversation: We hold a belief that those we work with, e Fear Conversation: We openly discuss problems in our team e Why Conversation: We share a common, explicit purpose that e Commitment Conversation: We regularly and reliably", "prev_page": {"page_num": 21, "segment_id": "00021"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 23, "segment_id": "00023"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversations", "teams", "conversation", "share", "where", "team", "will", "what", "five", "characteristics"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "management|devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Agile", "DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Five Conversations", "Trust Conversation", "Fear Conversation"], "key_concepts": ["Trust Conversation", "Fear Conversation", "Why Conversation", "Commitment Conversation", "Accountability Conversation"], "problem_statement": "Teams lacking in key characteristics such as trust, fearlessness, shared purpose, commitment, and accountability.", "solution_approach": "Implementing the Five Conversations to foster these essential team attributes.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00023", "page_num": 23, "segment": "Starting with\n\nthe Trust Conversation, and continuing with\nconversations addressing Fear, Why, Commitment, and Accountability, we\nwill show you in detail and step by step how to improve each of these ve\nkey attributes in your team. You’ll be able to use these methods whether\nyou are a junior developer or a senior executive, and we’ll explain how these\nimprovements will translate directly into improved results from your Agile,\nLean, and DevOps practices. We’ll illustrate how these methods work in\nreal life, with practical examples of conversations on each topic.\nChapters 3 through 7 are each divided into similar sections:\n\n• A motivational section explaining why the chapter’s featured\n\nconversation is important.\n\n• A story section\n\nintroducing a protagonist experiencing a\n\nproblematic conversation of this type.\n\n• One or more preparation sections that teach you methods\n\nintroduced in the chapter’s conversation.\n\n• An explanatory section (“e Conversation”) that describes one way\n\nto hold the chapter’s conversation.\n\n• A section that continues the story, where our protagonist learns\nfrom the problematic conversation and produces a better result.\n• Several example conversations that illustrate variations on the\n\nchapter’s conversation.\n\n• A case study, which tells a longer story about how the chapter’s\n\nconversation helped an organization improve.\n\nBut reading to the end of the book is only the beginning. Having\nlearned how to approach each of the key conversations, it will be up to you\nto practice what you’ve learned. If you do, we are condent you’ll nd the\neffort rewarded many times over. When you transform your conversations,\nyou transform your culture.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_nu