{"segment_id": "00035", "page_num": 35, "segment": "work. To those used to the dominant practices of the software factory, these\nleaders seemed like a crazed mob bent on creating mayhem. And yet there were\nstories of amazing results---elevated morale, rapid delivery, high quality---in\nthe teams brave enough to try these new methods.\n\nen, seventeen of the most visible proponents of the “lightweight\nsoftware” movement gathered at the ski resort in Snowbird, Utah, in February\n2001. As documented by James Highsmith, they were a diverse group,\nincluding the founders and advocates of Extreme Programming (XP), SCRUM,\nDSDM, Adaptive Software Development (ASD), Crystal, Feature-Driven\n\nDevelopment (FDD), Pragmatic Programming, and others.13 e question was,\ncould they nd common ground?\n\nAs it turns out, they did, and the result was, as Martin Fowler said, a “call to\narms,” a “rallying cry”:14 the Agile Manifesto, which continues to be widely\nused nearly two decades later.\n\nManifesto for Agile Software Development\n\nWe are uncovering better ways of developing software by doing it and\nhelping others do it. rough this work we have come to value:\n\nIndividuals and interactions over processes and tools\n•\n• Working software over comprehensive documentation\n• Customer collaboration over contract negotiation\n• Responding to change over following a plan\n\nat is, while there is value in the items on the right, we value the\n\nitems on the left more.15\n\ne group followed the manifesto with an often-overlooked set of twelve\naccompanying principles. is set of principles remains a useful touchpoint for\norganizations who aim for agility.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Development (FDD), Pragmatic Programming, and others.1