{"segment_id": "00042", "page_num": 42, "segment": "By 2009, the time was ripe for the humanistic software movement to broaden,\nand none knew it better than Patrick Debois, a frustrated consultant and\nproject manager in Belgium. He was annoyed because on project after project,\nhe saw how the deep divide between the responsibilities of developers and\nsystem administrators was holding back progress. ough many development\nteams were undoing the negative legacy of the software factory, they continued\nthe same old practices when interacting with the operators who deployed and\nran their code---minimal communication, low trust, and avoidance of difficult\nconversations. And just as they had within development teams, those\nbehaviors slowed progress and kept everyone from delivering the right working\nsoftware. It was clear that Agile development needed to move downstream:\n“e operations team needs to be agile, and it needs to be integrated into the\n\nproject.”19\n\nPatrick began trying to nd others interested in what he called “Agile\nSystem Administration.” ere were few takers at rst---at one conference,\n\nonly two people showed up to a session on the new topic.20 But there were\nothers thinking the same way, notably John Allspaw and Paul Hammond,\nheads of operations and engineering respectively at Flickr. eir presentation\n“10+ Deploys Per Day: Dev and Ops Cooperation at Flickr,” which called\npassionately for collaboration and trust between developers and operators,\n\nincreasing excitement and, soon thereafter,\n\nrapidly spread through Agile circles.21 Patrick watched a livestream of their talk\nwith\nlaunched the rst\n“DevOpsDays” conference in Ghent. e DevOps movement, armed with\npowerful values and technical tools, had been born.\n\nRespect, Trust, and No Blame\n\nere is no DevOps czar, and there was never a DevOps equivalent of\nSnowbird, so there is no denitive list of DevOps principles. But the seminal\nFlickr presentation is one of the clearest statements of goals for DevOps that\nwe are aware of, and it’s useful as a litmus test to gauge how teams that claim", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "By 2009, the time was ripe for the humanistic software movement to broaden,\nand none knew it better than Patrick Debois, a frustrated consultant and\nproject manager in Belgium. It was clear that Agile development needed to move downstream:\n“e operations team needs to be agile, and it needs to be...", "l2_summary": "By 2009, the time was ripe for the humanistic software movement to broaden,\nand none knew it better than Patrick Debois, a frustrated consultant and\nproject manager in Belgium. He was annoyed because on project after project,\nhe saw how the deep divide between the responsibilities of developers and\nsystem administrators was holding back progress. It was clear that Agile development needed to move downstream:\n“e operations team needs to be agile, and it needs to be integrated into the Patrick began trying to nd others interested in what he called “Agile\nSystem Administration.” ere were few takers at rst---at one conference, eir presentation\n“10+ Deploys Per Day: Dev and Ops Cooperation at Flickr,” which called\npassionately for collaboration and trust between developers and operators, ere is no DevOps czar, and there was never a DevOps equivalent of\nSnowbird, so there is no denitive...", "prev_page": {"page_num": 41, "segment_id": "00041"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 43, "segment_id": "00043"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["devops", "project", "agile", "software", "patrick", "development", "teams", "trust", "there", 