{"segment_id": "00043", "page_num": 43, "segment": "to be DevOps focused truly behave. e principles from the second half of that\npresentation are below (lightly edited to t nicely into a list):\n\nDevOps Principles\n\n1. Respect\n\na. Don’t stereotype\nb. Respect others’ expertise, opinions, and responsibilities\nc. Don’t just say “No”\nd. Don’t hide things\n\n2. Trust\n\na. Trust that everyone is doing their best for the business\nb. Share runbooks and escalation plans\nc. Provide knobs and levers\n3. Healthy attitude about failure\na. Failure will happen\nb. Develop your ability to respond to failure\nc. Hold fire drills\n\n4. Blame avoidance\n\na. No finger-pointing\nb. Devs: remember that broken code wakes people up\nc. Ops: provide constructive feedback on painful areas22\n\nNotice how explicit Allspaw and Hammond are about the crucial elements\nof trust, respect, and collaboration; this is clearly a movement for people, not\nmachines.\n\nat’s not to say that there aren’t key DevOps technical and team practices.\n\nese include:\n\n• Cross-functional team: Developers and operators work together in a\nsingle team rather than in separate groups with a handoff of completed\ncode from one to the other.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Don’t just say “No”\nd. Healthy attitude about failure\na. Failure will happen\nb.", "l2_summary": "to be DevOps focused truly behave. Respect others’ expertise, opinions, and responsibilities\nc. Don’t just say “No”\nd. Provide knobs and levers\n3. Healthy attitude about failure\na. Failure will happen\nb.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 42, "segment_id": "00042"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 44, "segment_id": "00044"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "