{"segment_id": "00060", "page_num": 60, "segment": "S: T  C\n\nFrom cover to cover, this book is about conversations, so it is worth taking a\nmoment to explain the range of conversation types where this material is\napplicable.\n\nThe first image that comes to mind when we say “conversation” is\nprobably a face-to-face encounter with two or more people in the same\nroom. However, most of us have a number of other types of communication\nchannels we use regularly. Email is ubiquitous. Chat systems such as Slack,\nMicrosoft Teams, and IRC (internet relay chat) are being adopted right and\nleft. Distributed meetings with video are increasingly common, a big step up\nfrom the voice-only conference call.\n\nWe believe the material in this book is useful across all these\nconversation modes, though it is worth considering the trade-os inherent\nin the dierent options. Figure 2.1 provides a useful visual reference for\nthese trade-os based on a model by Alistair Cockburn.16\n\nFigure 2.1: Eectiveness of Dierent Modes of Communication\n\nAs Cockburn says, “the most eective communication is person-toperson, face-to-face, as with two people at the whiteboard.”17 This scenario", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "The first image that comes to mind when we say “conversation” is\nprobably a face-to-face encounter with two or more people in the same\nroom. Figure 2.1: Eectiveness of Dierent Modes of Communication As Cockburn says, “the most eective communication is person-toperson, face-to-face, as with two...", "l2_summary": "From cover to cover, this book is about conversations, so it is worth taking a\nmoment to explain the range of conversation types where this material is\napplicable. The first image that comes to mind when we say “conversation” is\nprobably a face-to-face encounter with two or more people in the same\nroom. However, most of us have a number of other types of communication\nchannels we use regularly. Figure 2.1 provides a useful visual reference for\nthese trade-os based on a model by Alistair Cockburn.16 Figure 2.1: Eectiveness of Dierent Modes of Communication As Cockburn says, “the most eective communication is person-toperson, face-to-face, as with two people at the whiteboard.”17 This scenario", "prev_page": {"page_num": 59, "segment_id": "00059"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 61, "segment_id": "00061"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["face", "conversation", "communication", "cover", "book", "worth", "types", "material", "people", "most"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Slack", "Microsoft Teams"], "people": ["Alistair Cockburn"], "products": [], "technologies": ["email", "chat systems", "video meetings", "voice-only conference calls"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Slack", "Microsoft Teams"], "topics": ["conversation types", "communication modes", "trade-offs in communication"], "key_concepts": ["face-to-face conversations", "email", "chat systems", "video meetings", "voice-only conference calls"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00061", "page_num": 61, "segment": "is the most eective, because, among other attributes, it oers the\nmaximum possible nonverbal information to the two participants, and the\nfastest response rate. However, these same attributes can make it more\ndicult when you are learning to have dicult conversations and one or\nboth parties are feeling strong emotions. A red face\nis additional\ninformation, but it can also be intimidating and distracting.\n\nAs an opportunity for learning, asynchronous channels can oer some\nbenefits. One is that you’ll likely have a better record of what each party\nactually said, which can be a big help in performing a later conversational\nanalysis.* Even better, an asynchronous channel allows us to make multiple\ndrafts before responding. As an example, we’ve applied the Four Rs to draft\nemails, allowing us to use a technique we are learning and to incorporate the\ninsights into the email we finally sent.\n\nUltimately the skill you are after is the ability to apply these techniques\nface to face and in real time; making good use of the learning opportunities\nof asynchronous communication can help you gain that ability.\n\nThe Four Rs\n\nExperiences give us the opportunity to learn, but most people don’t take the\ntime to actually learn from them. We apply the Four Rs---Record, Reect,\nRevise, and Role Play---as our preferred way of learning from conversations.\n(As you can see in Figure 2.2, there are two additional Rs that can sneak in\nalong the way: Repeat and Role Reversal.)", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "A red face\nis additional\ninformation, but it can also be intimidating and distracting. As an opportunity for learning, asynchronous channels can oer some\nbenefits. (As you can see in Figure 2.2, there are two additional Rs that can sneak in\nalong the way: Repeat and Role Reversal.)", "l2_summary": "However, these same attributes can make it more\ndicult when you are learning to have dicult conversations and one or\nboth parties are feeling strong emotions. A red face\nis additional\ninformation, but it can also be intimidating and distracting. As an opportunity for learning, asynchronous channels can oer some\nbenefits. Ultimately the skill you are after is the ability to apply these techniques\nface to face and in real time; making good use of the learning opportunities\nof asynchronous communication can help you gain that ability. We apply the Four Rs---Record, Reect,\nRevise, and Role Play---as our preferred way of learning from conversations. (As you can see in Figure 2.2, there are two additional Rs that can sneak in\nalong the way: Repeat and Role Reversal.)", "prev_page": {"page_num": 60, "segment_id": "00060"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 62, "segment_id": "00062"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["learning", "face", "asynchronous", "four", "most", "attributes", "information", "make", "dicult", "have"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["Four Rs"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["effective communication", "asynchronous channels", "Four Rs technique"], "key_concepts": ["nonverbal information", "response rate", "emotional impact", "drafting emails", "conversational analysis"], "problem_statement": "challenges in having difficult conversations, especially when emotions are involved", "solution_approach": "using asynchronous channels and the Four Rs technique for learning", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00062", "page_num": 62, "segment": "Figure 2.2: e Four Rs\n\nTo start using the Four Rs, you will need to Record a conversation in\nwriting. In the next section, we describe our preferred method for this, the\nTwo-Column Conversational Analysis. It may be tempting to avoid pen and\npaper and just think about the conversation “in your mind’s eye,” or talk about\nit with a friend. Do not do this! e act of writing down the words on paper is an\ninherent part of the process because it forces your brain to think about the\nconversation at arm’s length, as if it were happening to someone else. is\ndistance is vital to gaining insights through reection and revision, as we’ll see\nlater.**\n\nAfter you have Recorded the conversation, it’s time to Reect on it, paying\nattention to the tool or technique you are trying to use at the time. For each of\nthe Five Conversations, we will suggest particular tools. With time and\npractice, you will move between them as the conversation requires, but to start\nwith, we recommend you use one tool or technique at a time. We will give you\nguidelines on how to score your conversation using the tool, and that reection\nwill lead you to possible improvements.\n\nHaving scored the conversation, Revise your conversation to try and\nproduce a better result. How will you know if you’ve improved? Repeat: take\nyour revised dialogue and Reect again. Did you improve your score from the\nrst time around? You may be surprised to nd that your revised version in\nfact shows no better scores than your original! Don’t be discouraged---this is\nvery common, especially as you are learning a new skill. It might take you half a\ndozen or more attempts to produce a revision that checks all the boxes of the\ntechnique.\n\nHaving created the dialogue for an alternative conversation, there’s still an\nimportant step remaining: Role Play. Find a friend who is willing to help, and\ntry saying your dialogue aloud, with your friend taking the part of your\nconversation partner. How does it feel to say the words out loud? Often what\nseems okay in writing feels unnatural coming out of your mouth. Perhaps the\nwords need to change, or perhaps you just need practice talking in a different\nway.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "To start using the Four Rs, you will need to Record a conversation in\nwriting. With time and\npractice, you will move between them as the conversation requires, but to start\nwith, we recommend you use one tool or technique at a time. Having scored the conversation, Revise your conversation to try...", "l2_summary": "Figure 2.2: e Four Rs To start using the Four Rs, you will need to Record a conversation in\nwriting. After you have Recorded the conversation, it’s time to Reect on it, paying\nattention to the tool or technique you are trying to use at the time. With time and\npractice, you will move between them as the conversation requires, but to start\nwith, we recommend you use one tool or technique at a time. We will give you\nguidelines on how to score your conversation using the tool, and that reection\nwill lead you to possible improvements. Having scored the conversation, Revise your conversation to try and\nproduce a better result.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 61, "segment_id": "00061"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 63, "segment_id": "00063"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversation", "will", "time", "need", "writing", "friend", "words", "tool", "technique", "dialogue"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "beginner", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["Two-Column Conversational Analysis"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Two-Column Conversational Analysis"], "topics": ["Four Rs", "Recording conversations", "Reflecting on conversations", "Revising conversations", "Role-playing"], "key_concepts": ["Writing down conversations", "Reflection and revision", "Using tools for analysis", "Improving dialogue through practice"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": "Describing a process to improve the quality of recorded conversations through reflection, revision, and role-playing.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00063", "page_num": 63, "segment": "Another good check on your progress is the other hidden R: Role Reversal.\nTrade places in your dialogue and have your friend say your words. How does it\nfeel to be in the other person’s shoes and to hear your revised language?\nFrequently, hearing your own words will give you clues as to how you can\nfurther tune the dialogue to feel more natural while keeping in place the skills\nyou are trying to practice.\n\nFollowing all of the Four Rs for a single conversation will offer the most\nlearning from that single experience. Following them for a series of\nconversations will dramatically increase the volume and pace of your learning\noverall, and should quickly give you and your team substantial practical gains.\n\nConversational Analysis\n\ne rst step of the Four Rs is, as we just explained, is to Record the\nconversations you want to improve. We’re about to show you a remarkable\ntechnique invented and used by Chris Argyris for capturing the key elements of\na conversation. We particularly like this method for two reasons: rst, it is\nclearly specied and mechanical, which appeals to our engineering brains; and\nsecond, it very naturally lends itself to the other three Rs: Reect, Revise, and\nRole Play.\n\nAt rst, conversational analysis may seem too simple to be valuable. But it\nis the fastest route to gaining signicant insights and improved conversations.\nWe use it throughout the book to illustrate how to make each of the Five\nConversations successful.\n\nYou Will Need\n\n1. A single sheet of ordinary writing paper (Don’t get more than a single\n\nsheet, for a reason we’ll explain shortly.).\n2. A pen, pencil, or other writing implement.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Another good check on your progress is the other hidden R: Role Reversal. Following all of the Four Rs for a single conversation will offer the most\nlearning from that single experience. Conversational Analysis", "l2_summary": "Another good check on your progress is the other hidden R: Role Reversal. How does it\nfeel to be in the other person’s shoes and to hear your revised language? Following all of the Four Rs for a single conversation will offer the most\nlearning from that single experience. Conversational Analysis e rst step of the Four Rs is, as we just explained, is to Record the\nconversations you want to improve. A single sheet of ordinary writing paper (Don’t get more than a single", "prev_page": {"page_num": 62, "segment_id": "00062"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 64, "segment_id": "00064"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["other", "will", "single", "conversations", "role", "dialogue", "words", "feel", "give", "more"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "management", "complexity": "beginner", "companies": [], "people": ["Chris Argyris"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["writing paper", "pen, pencil or other writing implement"], "topics": ["Role Reversal", "Conversational Analysis", "Four Rs"], "key_concepts": ["Role Reversal", "Conversational Analysis", "Four Rs"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00064", "page_num": 64, "segment": "at’s it, really. (We told you it was simple!) Again, don’t let yourself skip\nthe task of writing by saying you’ll imagine or remember the content---write it\ndown on a real piece of paper. You’ll be glad you did when your distance helps\nyou with a crucial insight.\n\nStep 1: Record Your Conversation\n\nink of a conversation you would like to improve. is can be one you had\nrecently, but it doesn’t have to be: you can analyze a conversation that occurred\nlong ago or (this is a favorite of ours) one that hasn’t happened yet that you’re\nworried about.\n\nNext, fold the paper down the middle the long way, creating two columns.\nIn the right-hand column, write down what each person in the conversation\nsaid. Don’t worry about getting every word right; you’re aiming for the sound\nand avor of the conversation, not exact quotes. On the other hand, try hard\nnot to editorialize or add anything to the words. You’re trying to record what a\nneutral listener or mechanical audio recorder would hear.\n\nIn the left-hand column, after you have written the dialogue, write what\nyou thought at the time as the words were spoken. Don’t hold back here; often\nin a difficult conversation, your thoughts will be very different from what you\nsaid, so include everything that crossed your mind, no matter how irrelevant or\nunfair it may seem. Important warning: you must not write anything that the\nother person thought.***\n\nTip: Keep It Short\nWe nd that newcomers to the conversational analysis method often write far\nmore than they need to, trying to capture every word of what might be a\nlengthy conversation. is is almost certainly unnecessary. If you concentrate\non the most emotionally charged part of the conversation for you, it is very\nlikely that you will be able to t that key section onto just one side of your\npiece of paper, which is exactly why we told you to prepare only one sheet.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Step 1: Record Your Conversation ink of a conversation you would like to improve. In the right-hand column, write down what each person in the conversation\nsaid.", "l2_summary": "Step 1: Record Your Conversation ink of a conversation you would like to improve. In the right-hand column, write down what each person in the conversation\nsaid. Don’t worry about getting every word right; you’re aiming for the sound\nand avor of the conversation, not exact quotes. In the left-hand column, after you have written the dialogue, write what\nyou thought at the time as the words were spoken. Important warning: you must not write anything that the\nother person thought.***", "prev_page": {"page_num": 63, "segment_id": "00063"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 65, "segment_id": "00065"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversation", "write", "what", "down", "paper", "hand", "told", "piece", "record", "would"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "other", "complexity": "beginner", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["conversation analysis", "writing down conversations", "improving communication"], "key_concepts": ["record dialogue accurately", "capture emotional content", "reflect on thoughts during conversation"], "problem_statement": "Improving the quality of a conversation by accurately recording and reflecting on it", "solution_approach": "Writing down the conversation and reflecting on one's thoughts", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00065", "page_num": 65, "segment": "Keeping the case very focused like this probably means that you’ll need to\nstart in the middle of the conversation rather than at the beginning. Don’t\nworry about this; it’s safe to assume that the reader knows the context of the\nconversation and what the participants said earlier, since the chief reader is\ngoing to be you!\n\nIf you nd it hard to keep your case this short, try making it even shorter,\n\njust half the page.**** e restriction to a very limited length will help you\ncreate a more valuable, analysis-friendly case.\n\nAn Example Two-Column Conversational Analysis\nLet’s look at a real conversation between the authors using the two-column\nanalysis technique. is example concisely illustrates all the key characteristics\nof a conversational analysis: it’s short, the thoughts and the actual words are\nboth included, and there are rich opportunities for learning by looking at the\ndifferences between the two columns.\n\nWhen you read someone else’s recorded conversation, read the columns in\nthe order they are recorded: read the right column rst so that you understand\nthe spoken dialogue, then go back and read the columns together so that you\nunderstand the inner dialogue that is happening along with the outer one. If\nyou just jump in and read left to right and top to bottom, as is natural in\nEnglish, you will hear that Squirrel is concerned about Jeffrey’s absence before\nJeffrey announces that he’ll be away. If you’re reading out loud, you might add\na reminder of the distinction between thoughts and speech: “Jeffrey says, ‘I’ll\nbe out of the country for our next scheduled online training.’” Squirrel thinks,\nOuch! Jeffrey usually sets up the phone and software connection, and so on. We\naren’t usually aware of the distinction between the inner and outer dialogue,\nwhich makes this format helpful but sometimes tricky to grasp at rst. Be\npatient: analyses become much easier to follow after you’ve recorded your own\nconversations a few times.\n\nJeffrey and Squirrel’s Conversation", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "An Example Two-Column Conversational Analysis\nLet’s look at a real conversation between the authors using the two-column\nanalysis technique. When you read someone else’s recorded conversation, read the columns in\nthe order they are recorded: read the right column rst so that you understand\nthe...", "l2_summary": "Keeping the case very focused like this probably means that you’ll need to\nstart in the middle of the conversation rather than at the beginning. An Example Two-Column Conversational Analysis\nLet’s look at a real conversation between the authors using the two-column\nanalysis technique. When you read someone else’s recorded conversation, read the columns in\nthe order they are recorded: read the right column rst so that you understand\nthe spoken dialogue, then go back and read the columns together so that you\nunderstand the inner dialogue that is happening along with the outer one. If\nyou just jump in and read left to right and top to bottom, as is natural in\nEnglish, you will hear that Squirrel is concerned about Jeffrey’s absence before\nJeffrey announces that he’ll be away. Jeffrey usually sets up the phone and software connection, and so on. Jeffrey and Squirrel’s Conversation", "prev_page": {"page_num": 64, "segment_id": "00064"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 66, "segment_id": "00066"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversation", "read", "jeffrey", "analysis", "case", "column", "columns", "recorded", "dialogue", "squirrel"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "programming", "complexity": "beginner", "companies": [], "people": ["Jeffrey", "Squirrel"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Conversational Analysis", "Short Case Studies"], "key_concepts": ["Two-Column Conversational Analysis", "Inner and Outer Dialogue"], "problem_statement": "Creating concise case studies for analysis", "solution_approach": "Using a two-column format to capture both spoken dialogue and inner thoughts", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00066", "page_num": 66, "segment": "What Squirrel thought and felt\n\nWhat Jeffrey and Squirrel said\n\nOuch! Jeffrey usually sets up the phone and\nsoftware connection. What do we do now?\n\nJeffrey: I’ll be out of the country for our next\nscheduled online training.\n\nSeems doomed. I think we’ll just have to give up.\n\nSquirrel: Okay, that means we can’t do it at your\noffice, I guess. Should we cancel?\n\nSure, but how will I get the technology to work?\nIt always seems fiddly when Jeffrey does it.\n\nJeffrey: Oh no, I’m sure I can dial in. Then you\ncan stay at home and won’t have to come to the\noffice.\n\nThat’s a good point---I’ll save on the commute\nstress.\n\nSquirrel: Yes, I guess you can join on the phone,\nand that would mean less travel for me. But I’ve\nnever done the software and phone setup.\n\nI’m far less confident than Jeffrey is about this.\n\nJeffrey: Don’t worry. The organizer sent us a link\nto a very helpful tutorial. You won’t have any\ntrouble.\n\nWhat will I do if I screw it up? Hundreds of\nattendees will be furious with me for delaying\nthe session they’ve paid for. I suppose I’ll just\nhave to give it a go.\n\nSquirrel: Well, I guess I can give it a try.\n\nIf you read just the right-hand column, you see a relatively calm\nconversation, with Squirrel expressing only mild doubts. at is indeed what\nyou would have observed if you’d been in the room with us. But the left-hand\ncolumn reveals far more about Squirrel’s inner fears and worries, with words\nlike “doomed” and “furious” illustrating his depth of feeling. ese unexpressed\nand perhaps undiscussable thoughts and feelings are exactly what we are going\nto concentrate on when we analyze cases using the techniques we are about to\nshow you.\n\nAnalyzing a Conversation:\nReflect, Revise, and Role Play", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": 