{"segment_id": "00107", "page_num": 107, "segment": "have built trust. Instead, Isaac managed to stay on the bottom rungs (Data,\nSelections, and Meanings), and after reection, discovered his own\nperceptions and feedback weren’t as accurate as he’d thought. Erin and\nIsaac now have shared stories about bug reports and Erin’s wish to be\nresponsive, which should help them work together with greater trust.\n\n“I just want the developers to be happy,” said Paul Joyce, founder of\nGeckoboard, a maker of dashboard software. “Productivity and prot can\ncome later. Right now, I’d just like to see them enjoying their jobs.” I\n(Squirrel) nodded and wondered what was making the engineers so\ndepressed.\n\nIt was certainly obvious to me, after only a day on site, that something\nwasn’t right in Geckoboard’s small tech team of ten. In the spacious tech\nroom, cluttered with board games and Ruby books, there were four\nstandups every day but little to report in each. Retrospectives were stilted\nand unproductive. Meetings dragged on for hours with little energy or\noutput. Conicts over technology or process were expressed indirectly, if at\nall. ere were plenty of projects underway---nearly as many as there were\ndevelopers to carry them out!---but none showed signs of being nished\nanytime soon. Ironically, one of the company’s own dashboards hung on\nthe wall of the tech room, displaying a huge graph that showed revenue\nremaining stubbornly at, missing every monthly target so far that year.\n\nUnsurprisingly, a similar malaise afflicted the rest of the business,\nwhose desks were crowded into the other room of the small London office.\nCustomer Service team members tried to talk positively about the product\nbut couldn’t tell users when to expect bug xes. Marketing and Sales\nwanted to splash new features to attract interest but had nothing to shout", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": f