{"segment_id": "00117", "page_num": 117, "segment": "Tara and Matt’s Conversation\n\nReminder: read the right-hand column first, then go back and read right to left.\n\nWhat Tara thought and felt\n\nWhat Tara and Matt said\n\nWhat a catastrophe!\n\nMatt: We can’t get to sorting or filtering in\nthe new report this sprint.\n\nWe have to get these features in---users are\ndemanding them.\n\nTara: What?! Don’t you want people to use it?\nThe user research told us very clearly that\nusers expect to be able to sort, at least.\n\nThis is just a way of saying that you don’t\ncare enough to get it done.\n\nMatt: Of course I do. But what we can deliver\nis limited by time and skill. A static report is\nwhat we’ve estimated as deliverable by Friday.\n\nWhat’s really happening is that you aren’t\npushing hard enough.\n\nTara: Why? Can’t the team work harder? Are\nthey not motivated enough?\n\nThis is nonsense. The engineers are lazy, and\nyou’re enabling them.\n\nMatt: That’s not the problem, Tara. Working\nharder would, in fact, be counterproductive---\nthey’d make silly mistakes and go slower. We\njust have to accept the estimates.\n\nIf our developers can’t get off their butts,\nmaybe someone from the outside will be able\nto show them how it’s done.\n\nTara: Okay, so maybe we should hire a\ncontractor. Would that get the report done?\n\nYou shoot down everything I propose. You’ve\nobviously just made up your mind that this\nisn’t happening.\n\nMatt: No. Remember the last contractor? She\ntook weeks to get up to speed. A new joiner\nwould slow us down this sprint, not speed us\nup.\n\nI had two blog posts and a webinar lined up to\npromote this feature. I’ll have to delay them\nall, just when we desperately need a new sales\nangle. I’m completely deflated.\n\nTara: I guess there’s no way out. We’ll just\nhave to wait before starting to promote the\nnew report.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Tara and Matt’s Conversation What Tara and Matt said Matt: That’s not the problem, Tara.", "l2_summary": "Tara and Matt’s Conversation What Tara thought and felt What Tara and Matt said Matt: We can’t get to sorting or filtering in\nthe new report this sprint. Matt: Of course I do. Matt: That’s not the problem, Tara.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 116, "segment_id": "00116"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 118, "segment_id": "00118"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["tara", "what", "matt", "just", "report", "have", "enough", "done", "would", "read"], "content_type": "practice", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Tara", "Matt"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Project Management", "Team Motivation", "User Research"], "key_concepts": ["Estimation Accuracy", "Team Performance", "User Expectations"], "problem_statement": "Mismatch between team estimation and user expectations regarding the new report's features.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00118", "page_num": 118, "segment": "I felt so ill after this conversation---nauseated, chest pounding---that I\nthought I must be having a heart attack. Why does Matt keep ignoring clear\nfeedback from our customers and refusing to ask the engineers to do more? I\nthought he cared about this business as much as I do, but I am really beginning\nto doubt that. If we don’t find a way to get these features completed, we’re\ngoing to miss our targets and go bankrupt, which terrifies me.\n\ne goal of the Fear Conversation is to discover hidden fears and make\nthem discussable. But how do they get hidden in the rst place?\n\nPart of the answer lies in a nondescript waiting room at Columbia\nUniversity, where researchers Bibb Latané and John Darley told a group of\nstudents to ll in a questionnaire as part of a psychology experiment. After\na few minutes, smoke began to ow into the room from a wall vent.\nEveryone kept writing; none of the students said a word. More smoke\nbillowed in, and it became hard to see. Nothing happened. No one made a\nmove to get help or even asked what was going on. Eventually, the acrid\nsmoke led to coughing and watering eyes, and one participant opened a\nwindow---but the dogged students continued writing, not discussing the\nunfolding crisis or seeking assistance until the experimenters stepped in\nand terminated the exercise.5\n\nfavorite term, pluralistic\n\ne phenomenon on display here is variously known as the bystander\nIndividuals are\neffect or, our\nuncomfortable with an event or observation, but since others are not\nacting, they (wrongly) assume that everyone else thinks the situation is\nnormal and safe, and don’t act themselves.*** A common fear is felt by\nsome or all of the people involved, but the expression of that fear is\ninhibited by the apparent consensus of the rest of the group. In other\n\nignorance.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "I\nthought he cared about this business as much as I do, but I am really beginning\nto doubt that. e goal of the Fear Conversation is to discover hidden fears and make\nthem discussable. But how do they get hidden in the rst place?", "l2_summary": "I felt so ill after this conversation---nauseated, chest pounding---that I\nthought I must be having a heart attack. I\nthought he cared about this business as much as I do, but I am really beginning\nto doubt that. e goal of the Fear Conversation is to discover hidden fears and make\nthem discussable. But how do they get hidden in the rst place? After\na few minutes, smoke began to ow into the room from a wall vent. Everyone kept writing; none of the students said a word.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 117, "segment_id": "00117"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 119, "segment_id": "00119"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["fear", "students", "smoke", "felt", "conversation", "thought", "more", "going", "hidden", "part"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Matt"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["bystander effect", "fear in business", "customer feedback"], "key_concepts": ["hidden fears", "plurality of ignorance", "group dynamics"], "problem_statement": "Matt ignoring customer feedback and the resulting fear among team members", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": 