{"segment_id": "00119", "page_num": 119, "segment": "words, people would rather die in a re than be the rst of the group to report\nthe smoke. at’s how strong pluralistic ignorance is.\n\ne smoke experiment tells us how people react to a singular\nfrightening occurrence, but what happens if a fear-inducing event occurs\nover and over with no action in response? In e Challenger Launch\nDecision: Risky Technology, Culture, and Deviance at NASA, Diane Vaughan\ninvestigates the space shuttle explosion in 1986;6 and Richard Feynman, in\nan appendix to the Rogers Commission Report, separately analyzed NASA’s\nresponses to problems observed during launches of the space shuttle on\n\ncold days.7 Both observed what Vaughan called the normalization of\ndeviance: Because the shuttle had launched without calamity over and over\nin cold conditions, NASA concluded that cracks observed in booster\ncomponents on such ights were not a problem. Although no cracks at all\nin the O-rings were expected, the fact that they were small in size led some\nengineers to conclude the danger they posed was low. Others had concerns\n---What reason could there be for believing that the next crack would be as\nsmall as the previous ones?---but did not speak up loudly enough to stop\nthe ights.\n\nIn fact, NASA managers believed so strongly in the safety of shuttle\nlaunches that they decided it was a good idea to put a civilian teacher on\nthe Challenger ight of January 28, 1986. at morning, with icicles\nforming on the launch tower, the boosters exploded exactly as the\nengineers had feared they would, killing the entire crew.\n\ne phenomenon of ickering tests, or tests that randomly fail, in\nsoftware development teams illustrates how normalization of deviance can\naffect a team, though with much less dire consequences. Developers build\nan automated test suite and run it on every code change. ey observe that\na few of the tests succeed most of the time but fail at seemingly random\nmoments. e natural conclusion is that the tests are erroneous---they\n“icker” occasionally due to some testing anomaly---and can be rerun if\nthey fail. If they succeed after a few tries, a release can go ahead. As many", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "In e Challenger Launch\nDecision: Risky Technology, Culture, and Deviance at NASA, Diane Vaughan\ninvestigates the space shuttle explosion in 1986;6 and Richard Feynman, in\nan appendix to the Rogers Commission Report, separately analyzed NASA’s\nresponses to problems observed during launches of the...", "l2_summary": "words, people would rather die in a re than be the rst of the group to report\nthe smoke. at’s how strong pluralistic ignorance is. In e Challenger Launch\nDecision: Risky Technology, Culture, and Deviance at NASA, Diane Vaughan\ninvestigates the space shuttle explosion in 1986;6 and Richard Feynman, in\nan appendix to the Rogers Commission Report, separately analyzed NASA’s\nresponses to problems observed during launches of the space shuttle on cold days.7 Both observed what Vaughan called the normalization of\ndeviance: Because the shuttle had launched without calamity over and over\nin cold conditions, NASA concluded that cracks observed in booster\ncomponents on such ights were not a problem. In fact, NASA managers believed so strongly in the safety of shuttle\nlaunches that they decided it was a good idea to put a civilian teacher on\nthe Challenger ight of January 28, 1986. ey observe...", "prev_page": {"page_num": 118, "segment_id": "00118"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 120, "segment_id": "00120"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["nasa", "shuttle", "tests", "would", "what", "deviance", "observed", "fail", "people", "report"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management|security", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["NASA"], "people": ["Diane Vaughan", "Richard Feynman"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "NASA", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Normalization of Deviance", "Pluralistic Ignorance", "Space Shuttle Challenger Disaster"], "key_concepts": ["pluralistic ignorance", "normalization of deviance", "risk management in organizations"], "problem_statement": "How organizational culture and decision-making processes can lead to ignoring safety risks.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00120", "page_num": 120, "segment": "of us know too well, the result is a production failure when the ickering\ntest turns out to be alerting us to a real but intermittent fault.\n\nIn both cases, that of the O-ring cracks and the ickering tests, we have\nan espoused norm for the group: “don’t y with broken equipment” and\n“don’t release when tests fail.” But repeated experience with a deviation\nfrom this norm---“ying safely with cracked rings” and “releasing despite\nintermittent failure”---leads to a new norm-in-use, with the organization\nignoring its own alarm systems. anks to pluralistic ignorance, expression\nof fear about the dangers of the new norm are repressed, and everything is\nin place for a disastrous outcome.\n\nSymptom\n\nEspoused Norm\n\nNorm-In-Use\n\nObvious bugs in\nproduction\n\nPass tests consistently\n\nTests can fail\nsometimes\n\nSystem alerts hourly\n\nClear alerts promptly\n\nIgnore known harmless\n\nalerts\n\nSprint end date\nextended\n\nEnd sprint cleanly and on\n\ntime\n\nLengthen sprint to\ncram in more\n\nLong standups\n\nKeep standups crisp and\n\nGive lengthy status\n\nspeedy\n\nreports\n\nLow code quality\n\nRefactor frequently\n\nTake shortcuts often\n\nToo many bugs\n\nFull test coverage\n\nTests are optional", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 7, "cols": 3, "data": [["Symptom", "Espoused Norm", "Norm-In-Use"], ["Obvious bugs in\nproduction", "Pass tests consistently", "Tests can fail\nsometimes"], ["System alerts hourly", "Clear alerts promptly", "Ignore known harmless\nalerts"], ["Sprint end date\nextended", "End sprint cleanly and on\ntime", "Lengthen sprint to\ncram in more"], ["Long standups", "Keep standups crisp and\nspeedy", "Give lengthy status\nreports"], ["Low code quality", "Refactor frequently", "Take shortcuts often"], ["Too many bugs", "Full t