{"segment_id": "00121", "page_num": 121, "segment": "Minimal iteration\n\nRelease frequently\n\nRelease only when\n\ncertain\n\nToo many admins\n\nGrant permissions only\n\nGrant admin rights on\n\nwhere needed\n\nrequest\n\nImprovement actions\n\nUse retrospectives\n\nToo busy to do the\n\nnot done\n\neectively\n\nactions\n\nUsers confused and\n\nInvolve customers/users in\n\nfrustrated\n\nthe design\n\nSkip user research\n\nTable 4.1: Examples of Normalized Deviance\n\ne Fear Conversation helps uncover the hidden fears in our team and\nreplaces normalization of deviance with the psychological safety needed to\nnotice and correct errors swiftly. To prepare for it, look for examples of a\ndangerous, deviant norm in your organization. To get you started, see our\nexamples in Table 4.1, where we list a number of symptoms you might\nobserve and, for each symptom, an espoused norm that is being violated\nand a norm-in-use that is actually being followed.\n\nAs you can see from the table, deviances of this kind may appear\nanywhere---in your software, your Agile processes, your product design,\nyour executive team. ey may seem easy to spot, but in practice, they’re\nnot so apparent; by denition, normalized deviance means the whole team,\nincluding you, has likely become blind to the variation from the espoused\nnorm.\n\nHave a colleague or friend from outside the team look for deviations\nwith you, as their outside perspective can help you identify problems you\ncan’t see from within. If your team experiences outages, severe bugs, or", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 3, "cols": 3, "data": [["Too many admins", "Grant permissions only\nwhere needed", "Grant admin rights on\nrequest"], ["Improvement actions\nnot done", "Use retrospectives\ne\u0000ectively", "Too busy to do the\nactions"], ["Users confused and\nfrustrated", "Involve customers/users in\nthe design", "Skip user research"]], "markdown": "| Too many admins | Grant permissions only\nwhere needed | Grant admin rights on\nrequest |\n|---|---|---|\n| Improvement actions\nnot done | Use retrospectives\ne\u0000ectively | Too busy to do the\nactions |\n| Users confused and\nfrustrated | Involve customers/users in\nthe design | Skip user research |"}], "table_count": 1, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Grant permissions only Table 4.1: Examples of Normalized Deviance To prepare for it, look for examples of a\ndangerous, deviant norm in your organization.", "l2_summary": "Grant permissions only Table 4.1: Examples of Normalized Deviance To prepare for it, look for examples of a\ndangerous, deviant norm in your organization. To get you started, see our\nexamples in Table 4.1, where we list a number of symptoms you might\nobserve and, for each symptom, an espoused norm that is being violated\nand a norm-in-use that is actually being followed. As you can see from the table, deviances of this kind may appear\nanywhere---in your software, your Agile processes, your product design,\nyour executive team. If your team experiences outages, severe bugs, or", "prev_page": {"page_num": 120, "segment_id": "00120"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 122, "segment_id": "00122"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["team", "norm", "table", "examples", "deviance", "release", "only", "grant", "where", "needed"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "devops|management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["Agile"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["DevOps practices", "Agile processes", "Team management"], "key_concepts": ["Normalized deviance", "Psychological safety", "Retrospectives"], "problem_statement": "Identifying and addressing normalized deviances in software development and Agile processes", "solution_approach": "Using the Fear Conversation to uncover hidden fears, improve team communication, and ensure adherence to best practices", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00122", "page_num": 122, "segment": "other serious failures, analyze these events with your colleague and seek\nexamples of violated norms. Reect on what deviations might have\npreceded these events, and identify practices your team can adopt to avoid\nthem in the future.\n\ne Trust Conversation is an exploration into unknown territory. You seek\nto understand your conversation partner’s story, which you couldn’t have\nknown at rst, and align your story with theirs. By contrast, the Fear\nConversation is more directed; thanks to your work in the previous section,\nyou will likely have some idea where there is normalization of deviance and\nyou will be looking for fears underlying that normalization. e danger is\nthat you can overdirect the Fear Conversation, focusing only on the fears\nand causes that seem likely from your point of view.\n\nIn this section, we’re going to show you a technique we’ve developed for\nunlocking your\ninner curiosity and overcoming your assumptions:\nCoherence Busting. As a bonus, when applied to the examples of normalized\ndeviance you found in the last section, this technique will give you a great\nhead start on the Fear Chart you’ll create in the Fear Conversation itself.\n\nThe Wrist Glance\n\nTo apply Coherence Busting, imagine yourself making a big proposal---one\nyou really want to sell to your audience. While you are talking, you notice\nthat the main stakeholder---the person you most hope to persuade---\nglances briey at her wrist. What do you do? And why?", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "e Trust Conversation is an exploration into unknown territory. You seek\nto understand your conversation partner’s story, which you couldn’t have\nknown at rst, and align your story with theirs. By contrast, the Fear\nConversation is more directed; thanks to your work in the previous section,\nyou...", "l2_summary": "other serious failures, analyze these events with your colleague and seek\nexamples of violated norms. e Trust Conversation is an exploration into unknown territory. You seek\nto understand your conversation partner’s story, which you couldn’t have\nknown at rst, and align your story with theirs. By contrast, the Fear\nConversation is more directed; thanks to your work in the previous section,\nyou will likely have some idea where there is normalization of deviance and\nyou will be looking for fears underlying that normalization. e danger is\nthat you can overdirect the Fear Conversation, focusing only on the fears\nand causes that seem likely from your point of view. As a bonus, when applied to the examples of normalized\ndeviance you found in the last section, this technique will give you a great\nhead start on the Fear Chart you’ll create in the Fear Conversation itself.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 121, "segment_id": "00121"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 123, "segment_id": "00123"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversation", "fear", "have", "section", "will", "events", "seek", "examples", "what", "story"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management|security", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Trust Conversation", "Fear Conversation", "Coherence Busting"], "key_concepts": ["normalized deviance", "trust conversation", "fear conversation", "coherence busting"], "problem_statement": "Identifying and addressing normalized deviance in a team or organization", "solution_approach": "Using the Trust Conversation to understand perspectives, and Coherence Busting to challenge assumptions", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00123", "page_num": 123, "segment": "Before reading on, spend a minute or so making a short list of actions\nyou might take and why you would take them in this situation. As you’ll see\nin a moment, it’s very important that you do not spend lots of time\nthinking about these actions; just jot down whatever comes to mind.\nDone? Your responses almost certainly resemble one of these:\n\n• I’ll speed up, because she has somewhere else to go.\n• I’ll ask if I’m covering the right material, because she must be bored.\n• I’ll jump to my most persuasive slide, because she must be\n\nquestioning my argument.\n\nIf your answers are anywhere close to these, congratulations! Your\nSystem 1 is in perfect working order---and it’s likely to betray you in\nsituations like this one.\n\nSystem 1 and System 2\n\nWe introduce the wrist-glance scenario to let you experience the decisionmaking heuristics that Daniel Kahneman describes in his book inking,\nFast and Slow. Kahneman models our consciousness as comprising two\nsystems: our fast, automatic, unconscious System 1, and our slow,\ndeliberate, effortful System 2.8 Part of what makes System 1 fast is the\nshortcuts it uses. Two of these shortcuts consistently arise with the wristglance example. e rst is that we assume that a coherent story must be\ncorrect. e second is that we limit the facts to what we can immediately\nrecall, a process Kahneman calls, “WYSIATI,” or “what you see is all there\nis.”9\n\nWe unconsciously construct a coherent story for what the glance means\n---for instance, “She has somewhere else to go.” is story is based on our\nrst thought about what the glance might mean (WYSIATI). e coherence\nin our story gives us the sense that our story is true. We then design our", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "• I’ll speed up, because she has somewhere else to go. System 1 and System 2 Kahneman models our consciousness as comprising two\nsystems: our fast, automatic, unconscious System 1, and our slow,\ndeliberate, effortful System 2.8 Part of what makes System 1 fast is the\nshortcuts it uses.", "l2_summary": "• I’ll speed up, because she has somewhere else to go. Your\nSystem 1 is in perfect working order---and it’s likely to betray you in\nsituations like this one. System 1 and System 2 Kahneman models our consciousness as comprising two\nsystems: our fast, automatic, unconscious System 1, and our slow,\ndeliberate, effortful System 2.8 Part of what makes System 1 fast is the\nshortcuts it uses. e rst is that we assume that a coherent story must be\ncorrect. e coherence\nin our story gives us the sense that our story is true.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 122, "segment_id": "00122"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 124, "segment_id": "00124"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["system", "what", "story", "because", "must", "glance", "kahneman", "fast", "spend", "actions"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "beginner", "companies": [], "people": ["Daniel Kahneman"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["System 1 and System 2", "Decision-making heuristics"], "key_concepts": ["WYSIATI", "Coherent story construction", "Automatic vs. deliberate thinking"], "problem_statement": "Understanding decision-making biases in a specific scenario", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00124", "page_num": 124, "segment": "actions in response to this story we made up, such as, “I’ll speed up.” is is\nthe key lesson of the wrist-glance example: we feel like we are responding\nto the reality of the situation, because WYSIATI and coherence cause us to\nmistake our single plausible story for the truth. But often we are wrong---\ndangerously, catastrophically wrong. In fact, have a look back at our\ndescription of the wrist glance. We wrote that the stakeholder briey\nglances at her wrist. We never mentioned a watch, but you almost certainly\nassumed there was one.\n\nis is why we need Coherence Busting.\n\nBusting the System 1 Story\n\nReturning to the wrist-glance exercise, now consider other possible\nmeanings of the wrist glance---all of the possible reasons: a nervous habit,\nan alert on her smartwatch, a rash on her hand, and lots more. Taking more\ntime to think allows you to activate your System 2 and come up with a long\nlist of possible reasons. is is Coherence Busting.\n\nWe nd it particularly helpful to stretch yourself and even include\nwildly implausible explanations: she has her plan for world domination\nwritten on her hand, the glance is a hidden signal to members of her secret\nsociety, etc. In fact, we recommend you start your Coherence Busting with\nthese extremely unlikely explanations because they are naturally\nhumorous, and laughter is inherently incompatible with the ght-or-ight\nresponse you may be feeling as you consider the fear-based, dangerously\ncoherent story that System 1 invented for you.\n\ne key to Coherence Busting is not that there are lots of options but\nthat the options are mutually incompatible. Once we can imagine\nconicting explanations, we are no longer trapped by the original coherent\nstory. ese options were always there, but we needed System 2, our\nconscious and effortful thought process, to bring them to the surface.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "is is why we need Coherence Busting. Busting the System 1 Story is is Coherence Busting.", "l2_summary": "But often we are wrong---\ndangerously, catastrophically wrong. In fact, have a look back at our\ndescription of the wrist glance. is is why we need Coherence Busting. Busting the System 1 Story is is Coherence Busting. e key to Coherence Busting is not that there are lots of options but\nthat the options are mutually incompatible.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 123, "segment_id": "00123"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 125, "segment_id": "00125"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["story", "wrist", "glance", "coherence", "busting", "system", "there", "possible", "explanations", "options"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["smartwatch"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["smartwatch"], "topics": ["WYSIATI", "coherence bias", "Coherence Busting"], "key_concepts": ["System 1 and System 2 thinking", "coherent story creation", "busting coherence"], "problem_statement": "Mistakenly assuming a single plausible story as the truth due to cognitive biases", "solution_approach": "Activating System 2 thinking to consider multiple possible explanations", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00125", "page_num": 125, "segment": "at’s not something we do naturally when we feel we already have a good\nexplanation, but it is vital to a successful Fear Conversation.\n\nApplying Coherence Busting\n\nYou can use Coherence Busting to help you prepare any time you are\napproaching a potentially difficult conversation, especially when you sense\nthat you may have some assumptions about how your conversation partner\nis thinking and feeling. (If you’re like us, you almost always have\nassumptions like this!) In Table 4.2 (page 86), we’ve provided some\nexamples of Coherence Busting in real situations.\n\nWhen preparing for the Fear Conversation, Coherence Busting can help\nus take a more curious, open attitude into the discussion that will help us\ndiscover and mitigate fears we never would have imagined. To prepare, list\nas many fears as you can that might underlie each of the normalized\ndeviances you came up with in the previous section. Be as broad as possible,\nengaging your System 2 to imagine fears that may seem unlikely or\ndownright silly. You may want to put your ideas on sticky notes or index\ncards to help you develop the Fear Chart in the next section.\n\nIf you think:\n\nConsider these alternatives:\n\nThe CEO ordered all teams to stop\n\ntesting.\n\nThe team writes perfect code, so tests\n\nMy team is too lazy to write tests.\n\nare superfluous.\n\nSomeone told them tests are useless.\nThey tried tests before and found them\n\ndicult.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 3, "cols": 2, "data": [["If you think:", "Consider these alternatives:"], ["My team is too lazy to write tests.", "The CEO ordered all teams to stop\ntesting.\nThe team writes perfect code, so tests\nare superfluous.\nSomeone told them tests are useless.\nThey tried tests before and found them\ndi\u0000cult."], 