{"segment_id": "00126", "page_num": 126, "segment": "Sales sta don’t care about\nquality, only deadlines.\n\nOur database vendor knows we\ncan’t switch providers and is\nmilking us for every penny it\ncan.\n\nThe Sales team is running a betting pool\nto see how ridiculous it can make the\ndevelopment targets.\n\nSalespeople believe code is always\n\nbuggy, so quality doesn’t matter.\nDeadlines are agreed to by executives,\nand Sales has no control over them.\n\nA rogue executive is trying to destroy\n\nthe company by driving away\ncustomers with ridiculous pricing.\nThe pricing matrix has a typo in it, and\nwe’re actually due a substantial\ndiscount.\n\nOur account manager, knowing we’re\ncash-strapped, negotiated a 50%\nreduction in the global rate increase.\n\nTable 4.2: Coherence Busting in Action\n\nScoring for Coherence Busting\n\nTo score a Two-Column Conversational Analysis with Coherence Busting as\nthe goal, look in your left-hand column and nd as many unsupported\nconclusions as you can about others’ thoughts or motivations. Look for\nsignals like the words “obviously” or “clearly,” as well as statements that\ndon’t have a rm basis in the right-hand column---for example, the\nassertion that the other person is denigrating your work without an explicit\nstatement, like “I don’t believe your project is up to scratch.” To check if\nyou’ve identied an unsupported conclusion, apply some Coherence", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 2, "cols": 2, "data": [["Sales sta\u0000 don’t care about\nquality, only deadlines.", "The Sales team is running a betting pool\nto see how ridiculous it can make the\ndevelopment targets.\nSalespeople believe code is always\nbuggy, so quality doesn’t matter.\nDeadlines are agreed to by executives,\nand Sales has no control over them."], ["Our database vendor knows we\ncan’t switch providers and is\nmilking us for every penny it\ncan.", "A rogue executive is trying to destroy\nthe company by driving away\ncustomers with ridiculous pricing.\nThe pricing matrix has a typo in it, and\nwe’re actually due a substantial\ndiscount.\nOur account manager, knowing we’re\ncash-strapped, negotiated a 50%\nreduction in the global rate increase."]], "markdown": "| Sales sta\u0000 don’t care about\nquality, only deadlines. | The Sales team is running a betting pool\nto see how ridiculous it can make the\ndevelopment targets.\nSalespeople believe code is always\nbuggy, so quality doesn’t matter.\nDeadlines are agreed to by executives,\nand Sales has no control over them. |\n|---|---|\n| Our database vendor knows we\ncan’t switch providers and is\nmilking us for every penny it\ncan. | A rogue executive is trying to destroy\nthe company by driving away\ncustomers with ridiculous pricing.\nThe pricing matrix has a typo in it, and\nwe’re actually due a substantial\ndiscount.\nOur account manager, knowing we’re\ncash-strapped, negotiated a 50%\nreduction in the global rate increase. |"}], "table_count": 1, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Sales sta don’t care about\nquality, only deadlines. Table 4.2: Coherence Busting in Action Scoring for Coherence Busting", "l2_summary": "Sales sta don’t care about\nquality, only deadlines. Our database vendor knows we\ncan’t switch providers and is\nmilking us for every penny it\ncan. The Sales team is running a betting pool\nto see how ridiculous it can make the\ndevelopment targets. Deadlines are agreed to by executives,\nand Sales has no control over them. Table 4.2: Coherence Busting in Action Scoring for Coherence Busting", "prev_page": {"page_num": 125, "segment_id": "00125"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 127, "segment_id": "00127"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["coherence", "sales", "busting", "column", "quality", "deadlines", "ridiculous", "believe", "pricing", "look"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Sales team", "Account manager", "Rogue executive"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["Database vendor"], "topics": ["Sales team behavior", "Internal company issues", "Account management challenges"], "key_concepts": ["Coherence Busting", "Unsupported conclusions", "Sales targets and deadlines"], "problem_statement": "Internal conflicts and misunderstandings within the organization affecting project quality and customer satisfaction.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00127", "page_num": 127, "segment": "Busting by trying to think up alternative explanations for the observations\nthat led you to the conclusion; if you succeed in developing plausible\nsubstitutes, the conclusion must not be supported. Give yourself one point\nfor each unsupported conclusion. Your goal should be to keep your score as\nlow as possible.\n\nThe Conversation: The Fear Chart\n\nWith normalization of deviance and Coherence Busting under our belts,\nwe’re ready to have the Fear Conversation.****\n\nOur rst task in the Fear Conversation is to make all the fears we can\nthink of discussable. is is where Coherence Busting will help---especially if\nthe whole team has been able to do it. (If they haven’t, consider introducing\nthe idea of Coherence Busting at the start of the conversation, inviting\neveryone to take ve minutes to engage their System 2 to generate ideas.)\nen we will move on to ltering the key fears and, nally, mitigating those\nfears. You’ll be constructing a Fear Chart as you go (Figure 4.1 at the end of\nthis section, on page 90, shows how your chart might look at the end of\nthis exercise).\n\nStep 1. Make visible all the fears identied so far (by you alone or by\nthe whole team). We like sticky notes because you can move them\naround easily, but writing on a whiteboard or putting index cards on\na table will work too. Solicit more fears from the group, perhaps by\nasking for more extreme versions of identied fears (“If a bug is bad,\nwould an outage be worse?”) or by asking for the opposite of\nidentied fears (“We’re afraid we’ll lose staff. Are we also afraid of\ngrowing the team too fast?”).\n\nStep 2. Ask the group for more items to add or for ways to combine\nexisting cards. Add new fears without editing them---our goal is to\nget all the ideas of the group identied, not to lter any out.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, 