], "key_concepts": ["Normalization of Deviance", "Coherence Busting", "Fear Chart"], "problem_statement": "Managing and mitigating fears in a team or organization", "solution_approach": "Identifying, discussing, and mitigating fears through structured processes", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00128", "page_num": 128, "segment": "Almost always, some of the identied fears will reinforce each\nother and/or some will be completely incompatible. Reect this by\nputting cards near each other or on top of one another, or by using\nlabelled arrows to connect groups of cards, or use anything else that\nhelps you see connections. Be sure you don’t leave out quiet team\nmembers. Ask specically whether a grouping is okay with those\nwho developed it.\n\nStep 3. Now it’s time to lter the items that are worth pursuing and\nmitigating from those that we can safely live with. We like to use\ndot voting***** to identify the fears that we want to mitigate, but\nyou can use another method if you prefer. e more outrageous\nideas that helped activate your System 2, such as those involving\naliens or secret societies, will almost certainly not survive this\nprocess, having served their purpose in encouraging creativity. You\nwill wind up with a subset of the fears that the group wants to deal\nwith---those that are most concerning or most consequential.\n\nStep 4. We’ll achieve the goal of the Fear Conversation if we can\nidentify mitigations that help us reduce each of the target fears.\nMitigations may include things like:\n\n• Fear of buggy releases angering customers:\n\n∘ Discuss quality versus speed trade-offs with customers or\n\ntheir internal proxies, and agree to expectations.\n∘ Increase manual and automated testing coverage.\n∘ Agree with executives that they will handle any angry\n\ncustomers while the team improves quality.\n\n• Fear of missing deadlines:\n\n∘ Understand deadline drivers and negotiate reduced scope or\nchanged dates through conversation with Marketing or Sales.\n\n∘ Reduce scope with customer approval.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null,