{"segment_id": "00143", "page_num": 143, "segment": "The Why\nConversation\n\nS\n\no far, we have added tools to our conversational toolkit that can help us\nto build trust and reduce fear. ese techniques address issues that\nprevent collaboration and reduce problem solving that might trap any team\nin the factory mind-set. Removing barriers to success was our rst goal, but\nwith the next tool, we begin the process of building up a positive\nframework for our team to work within. Building a Why gives our company\na strategic direction that guides large and small decisions, and provides a\nstrong motive for success. Independent decision-making and team\nmotivation were not concerns in the noncollaborative factory, but they are\nvital once we break free of it and begin to operate autonomously.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "o far, we have added tools to our conversational toolkit that can help us\nto build trust and reduce fear. ese techniques address issues that\nprevent collaboration and reduce problem solving that might trap any team\nin the factory mind-set. Removing barriers to success was our rst goal, but\nwith...", "l2_summary": "o far, we have added tools to our conversational toolkit that can help us\nto build trust and reduce fear. ese techniques address issues that\nprevent collaboration and reduce problem solving that might trap any team\nin the factory mind-set. Removing barriers to success was our rst goal, but\nwith the next tool, we begin the process of building up a positive\nframework for our team to work within. Building a Why gives our company\na strategic direction that guides large and small decisions, and provides a\nstrong motive for success. Independent decision-making and team\nmotivation were not concerns in the noncollaborative factory, but they are\nvital once we break free of it and begin to operate autonomously.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 142, "segment_id": "00142"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 144, "segment_id": "00144"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["team", "reduce", "factory", "success", "begin", "building"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Building a Why", "Trust and Collaboration", "Strategic Direction"], "key_concepts": ["collaboration", "problem solving", "team motivation", "positive framework"], "problem_statement": "Removing barriers to success in a team", "solution_approach": "Implementing tools for trust, reducing fear, and building a strategic direction", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00144", "page_num": 144, "segment": "Our central message in this chapter is that the Why you build must not\nonly explain the impetus for your collective action as a team but be created\njointly, with all those involved. An executive who imposes a Why from\nabove---or worse, with only a sham consultation---does more harm than\ngood. Jointly creating a purpose means that a chief architect can\nconcentrate on pointing to the cloud as the next evolutionary step, that a\ntech lead can get her whole team behind the quarterly goal, and that a\ntester can decide with condence which component she should automate\ntests for next.\n\nWhen you nish working through these methods, you will be able to:\n\n• Distinguish interests from positions, and uncover the former during\na conversation that is stuck in an endless debate involving the\nlatter.\n\n• Combine advocacy and inquiry in a way that lets you be curious\nabout the other person’s view while transparently sharing your\nown.\n\n• Jointly design a solution---such as a team Why---by using the\nprevious two techniques together with clear decision-making and a\ntimeboxed discussion, allowing all participants to be heard and\nyielding a result that everyone can say they contributed to.\n\nDon’t Start with Why\n\nSimon Sinek, in one of the most-watched TED Talks ever, argues\npassionately that to be successful, organizations must always lead with\ntheir Why, the central reason for their existence and action. “What” and\n“How,” the strategy and tactics that dene their route to the Why, come\nlater; to succeed, customers, employees, and investors need to rst hear,\n\nunderstand, and align with the organization’s purpose.1\n\nIn his talk and his follow-up book, Start with Why, Sinek cites a number\n\nof examples to support his argument:", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Our central message in this chapter is that the Why you build must not\nonly explain the impetus for your collective action as a team but be created\njointly, with all those involved. An executive who imposes a Why from\nabove---or worse, with only a sham consultation---does more harm than\ngood. In...", "l2_summary": "Our central message in this chapter is that the Why you build must not\nonly explain the impetus for your collective action as a team but be created\njointly, with all those involved. An executive who imposes a Why from\nabove---or worse, with only a sham consultation---does more harm than\ngood. Jointly creating a purpose means that a chief architect can\nconcentrate on pointing to the cloud as the next evolutionary step, that a\ntech lead can get her whole team behind the quarterly goal, and that a\ntester can decide with condence which component she should automate\ntests for next. When you nish working through these methods, you will be able to: understand, and align with the organization’s purpose.1 In his talk and his follow-up book, Start with Why, Sinek cites a number", "prev_page": {"page_num": 143, "segment_id": "00143"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 145, "segment_id": "00145"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["team", "jointly", "central", "must", "only", "action", "purpose", "next", "lead", "start"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Simon Sinek"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["joint creation of purpose", "Why you build", "executive imposition"], "key_concepts": ["jointly creating a purpose", "distinguishing interests from positions", "combining advocacy and inquiry"], "problem_statement": "The challenge of effectively communicating the 'Why' in an organization", "solution_approach": "Methods for creating a shared 'Why' that involves all team members, distinguishing between interests and positions, and combining advocacy with inquiry", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00145", "page_num": 145, "segment": "• Explorer Ernest Shackleton, before attempting the rst crossing of\nthe Antarctic in 1914, reportedly advertised for people to join him\nthus: “Men wanted for hazardous journey. Small wages, bitter cold,\nlong months of complete darkness, constant danger, safe return\n\ndoubtful. Honour and recognition in case of success.”2\n\n• In a major rebranding in 1997, Apple’s ads urged us to “think\ndifferent,” without mentioning their products at all. Establishing\ntheir company’s mission so clearly with customers, and in a way\ncompletely divorced from their existing computer products, allowed\nthem to dominate new categories in the following decade, such as\nmusic players, smartphones, and tablets.\n\n• Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.’s inspiring 1963 speech described a\nvision of a new world where people would “... be judged not by the\n\ncolor of their skin but by the content of their character.”3 King had\nalmost nothing to say about how his listeners would reach this\npromised land---and crucially, the speech was called “I Have a\nDream,” not “I Have a Plan.” Yet Dr. King managed to captivate and\nconvince an audience of more than 250,000 people solely by talking\nabout his beliefs.\n\nIn each case, a bold leader attracted followers and believers with a\ncompelling argument for what the group was aiming to accomplish and\nachieved dramatic success, without dwelling on strategy or tactics. In our\nexperience, a powerful Why also helps with a smaller, tactical change in just\nthe same way.\n\nIt seems to follow naturally that if we want our team to scale similar\nheights, we need to share with them a genuine commitment to an inspiring\nWhy. With a clear direction and internal commitment, they will be able to\nself-organize and succeed just like Shackleton, Apple, and King. Right?\n\nWith the utmost respect, we have to disagree. Starting with Why is\n\ndangerous and unlikely to succeed.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Honour and recognition in case of success.”2 Martin Luther King Jr.’s inspiring 1963 speech described a\nvision of a new world where people would “... King managed to captivate and\nconvince an audience of more than 250,000 people solely by talking\nabout his beliefs.", "l2_summary": "• Explorer Ernest Shackleton, before attempting the rst crossing of\nthe Antarctic in 1914, reportedly advertised for people to join him\nthus: “Men wanted for hazardous journey. Honour and recognition in case of success.”2 • In a major rebranding in 1997, Apple’s ads urged us to “think\ndifferent,” without mentioning their products at all. Martin Luther King Jr.’s inspiring 1963 speech described a\nvision of a new world where people would “... color of their skin but by the content of their character.”3 King had\nalmost nothing to say about how his listeners would reach this\npromised land---and crucially, the speech was called “I Have a\nDream,” not “I Have a Plan.” Yet Dr. King managed to captivate and\nconvince an audience of more than 250,000 people solely by talking\nabout his beliefs.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 144, "segment_id": "00144"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 146, "segment_id": "00146"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["king", "people", "have", "shackleton", "case", "success", "apple", "without", "products", "inspiring"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Apple"], "people": ["Ernest Shackleton", "Dr. Martin Luther King Jr."], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Leadership", "Inspiring Vision", "Branding"], "key_concepts": ["Compelling Why", "Clear Mission", "Self-Organization"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00146", "page_num": 146, "segment": "Yes, a clear purpose must be agreed upon if a team is to make\nproductive use of techniques like iterative delivery and periodic reection\nfor improvement. And yes, alignment on this purpose must come before we\ncan agree to scope, milestones, deadlines, targets, and everything else that\nwe need to make the Agile engine go. at’s the reason that the next two\nconversations, Why and Commitment, come in that order; and we will have\na lot to say in both about how to build the internal commitment needed to\nalign on the team’s and the organization’s Why.\n\nBefore the Why\n\nBut far too often, we have seen leaders try to inspire their teams without\nrst having the Trust and Fear Conversations---and with dismal results.\nWithout aligned stories that let everyone share a model of expected\nbehavior, no one is ready to believe there is anyone steering the ship, much\nless believe there is anyone prepared to agree on a direction. And when\nunfettered fears dominate the team’s thinking, they can’t make room for\nthe Joint Design of goals that forms the heart of the Why Conversation.\n\nWe’re reminded of one team we worked with right after the launch of a\nsoftware-as-a-service product that had taken nearly a year to build. Lack of\niteration and customer\ninvolvement meant that the product was\noundering, with salespeople unable to close even a single deal. Team\nmembers looked and felt demoralized, and no one seemed to know how to\nx the software to make it marketable. It seemed obvious that what this\ngroup needed was a good dose of Sinek-style Why to help them re-engage\nwith customers and iterate their way to a solution.\n\nBut when we dug deeper, we quickly found that there were underlying\nissues of trust and fear that meant this group was in no way ready for the\nWhy Conversation. Leaders had made unilateral and unpopular decisions\nabout team organization and product marketing. is had lead to badly\nmisaligned stories about their motivation. And shortcuts like skipping code", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "at’s the reason that the next two\nconversations, Why and Commitment, come in that order; and we will have\na lot to say in both about how to build the internal commitment needed to\nalign on the team’s and the organization’s Why. Team\nmembers looked and felt demoralized, and no one seemed to know...", "l2_summary": "Yes, a clear purpose must be agreed upon if a team is to make\nproductive use of techniques like iterative delivery and periodic reection\nfor improvement. at’s the reason that the next two\nconversations, Why and Commitment, come in that order; and we will have\na lot to say in both about how to build the internal commitment needed to\nalign on the team’s and the organization’s Why. And when\nunfettered fears dominate the team’s thinking, they can’t make room for\nthe Joint Design of goals that forms the heart of the Why Conversation. We’re reminded of one team we worked with right after the launch of a\nsoftware-as-a-service product that had taken nearly a year to build. Team\nmembers looked and felt demoralized, and no one seemed to know how to\nx the software to make it marketable. Leaders had made unilateral and unpopular decisions\nabout team organization and product marketing.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 145, "segment_id": "00145"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 147, "segment_id": "00147"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["team", "make", "there", "product", "purpose", "must", "like", "come", "agree", "conversations"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management|programming", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": ["software-as-a-service product"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Agile"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Agile methodology", "team alignment", "trust and fear in teams"], "key_concepts": ["Why conversation", "commitment", "iteration delivery", "customer involvement"], "problem_statement": "Lack of alignment on purpose and trust issues within a team", "solution_approach": "Conducting Why and Commitment conversations, addressing underlying trust and fear issues", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00147", "page_num": 147, "segment": "reviews and pushing features live without product owner involvement had\nled to understandable fears from the team about code and release quality.\nTrying to give this group an inspiring Why at this point would have been\nlike Captain Bligh delivering a motivational speech to the crew of the\nBounty just before the mutiny.\n\nAfter lots of intense work with the organization, we unearthed a\nnumber of actions that helped to improve trust and mitigate fears,\nincluding:\n\n• Redening the team lead’s role and coaching him in collaborative\nleadership, including making and fullling promises to include the\nwhole team in decision-making.\n\n• Making quality fears discussable and reshaping the release process\n\nto address them.\n\n• Removing an\n\nineffective senior\n\nleader whose actions had\n\nundermined trust.\n\nOnly after taking these actions was the team able to have a meaningful\nWhy Conversation, discussing company and team goals and the reasons\nwhy the product launch had failed so badly, and then beginning the process\nof addressing missing features through iterative delivery (which is no\nlonger a source of fear). e product is now selling briskly.\n\nAs you can see from this example, a team without a Why can be\nmisaligned and directionless, while a powerful Why provides psychological\nsafety and a clear alignment on goals. ese techniques for jointly\ndesigning a powerful Why rely on a foundation of solid trust and reduced\nfears so that the team can work and build on the skills learned in the\nprevious chapters, like Coherence Busting and TDD for People.\n\nSo ensure you’ve got those bases covered before proceeding. If you have,\n\nlet’s get started!", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "reviews and pushing features live without product owner involvement had\nled to understandable fears from the team about code and release quality. • Making quality fears discussable and reshaping the release process leader whose actions had", "l2_summary": "reviews and pushing features live without product owner involvement had\nled to understandable fears from the team about code and release quality. After lots of intense work with the organization, we unearthed a\nnumber of actions that helped to improve trust and mitigate fears,\nincluding: • Redening the team lead’s role and coaching him in collaborative\nleadership, including making and fullling promises to include the\nwhole team in decision-making. • Making quality fears discussable and reshaping the release process leader whose actions had As you can see from this example, a team without a Why can be\nmisaligned and directionless, while a powerful Why provides psychological\nsafety and a clear alignment on goals.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 146, "segment_id": "00146"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 148, "segment_id": "00148"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["team", "fears", "product", "have", "actions", "trust", "making", "features", "without", "release"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management|devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Captain Bligh", "team lead"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Agile"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["team trust", "motivational leadership", "release quality"], "key_concepts": ["Why conversation", "psychological safety", "coherent decision-making"], "problem_statement": "Fears and lack of trust among the development team due to frequent releases without product owner involvement.", "solution_approach": "Improving trust through collaborative leadership, addressing quality fears, and removing ineffective leaders.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00148", "page_num": 148, "segment": "Bobby’s Why Story\n\nI’m Bobby, the team lead for a group in New York building the embedded\nsoftware that runs inside an e-learning tablet for kids. Darius is my counterpart\nin hardware, building the tablet itself. Between us we’re responsible for shipping\nnew versions of the product, from chips to firmware to apps. The problem is that\nDarius is seven time zones away, so we almost never get to talk live. I think his\nteam should shift their working hours so we overlap more. I woke up at the\ncrack of dawn to discuss this with Darius on the phone, but the conversation\nwent awry quickly. I’ve recorded it and will be analyzing it to find out what went\nwrong.\n\nBobby and Darius’s Conversation\n\nReminder: read the right-hand column first, then go back and read right to left.\n\nWhat Bobby thought and felt\n\nWhat Bobby and Darius said\n\nSurely, you’ll see the benefits of increasing\ncommunication.\n\nBobby: We’ve got to get more overlap between\nthe teams. Would you be willing to start and\nfinish later to make that work?\n\nWell, stonewalling isn’t going to get us\nanywhere.\n\nDarius: No, that won’t be possible.\n\nI don’t think Santa Claus is going to shift his\ndelivery date for us. Our mission is to make\nkids happy and smart; missing Christmas\nwould achieve neither!\n\nBobby: Huh?! But our communication has to\nimprove. The product has to be ready on time\nfor Christmas, and the delays are killing our\nplan.\n\nI can’t believe this. Our documents are\nperfectly clear! His engineers just don’t want\nto read them.\n\nDarius: You don’t understand. Staying late\nwon’t fix the delays when the problem is bad\ndocumentation.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Bobby and Darius’s Conversation What Bobby and Darius said Darius: You don’t understand.", "l2_summary": "Bobby and Darius’s Conversation What Bobby thought and felt What Bobby and Darius said Bobby: We’ve got to get more overlap between\nthe teams. Darius: No, that won’t be possible. Darius: You don’t understand.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 147, "segment_id": "00147"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 149, "segment_id": "00149"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["bobby", "darius", "what", "read", "team", "building", "tablet", "kids", "product", "problem"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Bobby", "Darius"], "products": ["e-learning tablet for kids"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["cross-team communication", "time zone differences", "product development timeline"], "key_concepts": ["team coordination", "communication barriers", "project timelines"], "problem_statement": "Communication issues between teams working on different parts of an e-learning tablet for kids, specifically due to time zone differences.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00149", "page_num": 149, "segment": "I’ll try again to make the case.\n\nBobby: If it is documentation that’s at fault\n---and I don’t think it is---how can we ever find\nout where it’s wrong if we don’t talk more?\n\nI agree, talking to you won’t help. You make a\nbrick wall look transparent!\n\nDarius: It won’t help. If we get good specs, we\ncan build to them. That’s the only way.\n\nI’m out of options. I can’t do anything when\nyou’re digging in your heels.\n\nBobby: I give up. If you won’t move your\nworking hours voluntarily, I’ll have to ask our\nCEO to make you do it.\n\nDarius is terse and uncommunicative in email and chat, but I thought he’d\nopen up on the phone. Boy, was I wrong! He’s even more stubborn in real life.\nSeems to me that we don’t agree about the causes of delays or how to\ncommunicate better, or even why we’re making these tablets in the first place. I\ndon’t see how I can work with Darius at all.\n\nYour purpose in the Trust and Fear Conversations was to uncover and make\ndiscussable previously hidden ideas (stories and fears, respectively). You\nmight imagine that the Why Conversation will be easier, because you can\njust tell your colleagues all the inspiring reasons that their work is\nimportant. Right?\n\nSadly, that’s very unlikely to work, because odds are that your inspiring\nreasons are not going to be meaningful to some or all of the rest of the\nteam. We know of one executive in the banking industry who spent years\ntelling everyone that his company existed to make markets efficient. at\nwas true, and the company was indeed very successful at removing nancial\ninefficiencies; but this Why made exactly zero impact on product design,", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Bobby: If it is documentation that’s at fault\n---and I don’t think it is---how can we ever find\nout where it’s wrong if we don’t talk more? Darius: It won’t help. I\ndon’t see how I can work with Darius at all.", "l2_summary": "I’ll try again to make the case. Bobby: If it is documentation that’s at fault\n---and I don’t think it is---how can we ever find\nout where it’s wrong if we don’t talk more? I agree, talking to you won’t help. You make a\nbrick wall look transparent! Darius: It won’t help. I\ndon’t see how I can work with Darius at all.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 148, "segment_id": "00148"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 150, "segment_id": "00150"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["make", "darius", "work", "bobby", "wrong", "more", "agree", "help", "even", "because"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Bobby", "Darius"], "products": ["tablets"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Communication Issues", "Project Delays", "Team Dynamics"], "key_concepts": ["Documentation issues", "Specs and design", "Working hours flexibility", "Trust and fear in team communication"], "problem_statement": "Communication and trust issues between team members leading to project delays", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00150", "page_num": 150, "segment": "hiring, or employee motivation, because it just didn’t matter to most\nsoftware developers and product managers working there.\n\nInstead, we are going to suggest you do something much harder: jointly\ndesign the Why for your organization. is is harder than it seems, because\nit means negotiating and compromising, one step back and two steps (we\nhope) forward---a seeming waste of time. It’s also harder because it means\nthe death of the ego for all sides; we can no longer believe that we are the\nonly source of truth and direction in our working lives. It’s especially\ndifficult for executives or founders who sincerely believe that they are the\nonly ones who know, or should know, the right direction for the\norganization. But Joint Design is the only way to create internal\ncommitment and self-organization in a team.*\n\nWe will describe Joint Design itself in the next section, but before that,\nwe have two specic techniques to offer: Interests, Not Positions and\nCombining Advocacy and Inquiry. Both are useful in any situation where you\nneed to collaborate with others in an area of contention.\n\nInterests, Not Positions\n\nArthur Martirosyan, a negotiator for the humanitarian organization Mercy\nCorps, tells the story of a successful negotiation using the “interests, not\npositions” technique from the book Getting to Yes: Negotiating Agreement\nwithout Giving In:4 An oil company discovered large new reserves in postwar\nIraq and prepared to begin drilling immediately. Unfortunately, the oil lay\ndirectly under elds being tilled by tenant farmers, who were not ready to\ngive up their crops. Even more unfortunately, their threats to arm\nthemselves and shoot up the company’s office were completely credible in a\nsociety still recovering from a civil war and riven by sectarian violence. is\nseemed to be an intractable standoff, with neither side willing to give up\ntheir positions: the oil company wanted to drill, and the farmers wanted to\nfarm. Stalemate!", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Instead, we are going to suggest you do something much harder: jointly\ndesign the Why for your organization. But Joint Design is the only way to create internal\ncommitment and self-organization in a team.* Interests, Not Positions", "l2_summary": "Instead, we are going to suggest you do something much harder: jointly\ndesign the Why for your organization. It’s also harder because it means\nthe death of the ego for all sides; we can no longer believe that we are the\nonly source of truth and direction in our working lives. It’s especially\ndifficult for executives or founders who sincerely believe that they are the\nonly ones who know, or should know, the right direction for the\norganization. But Joint Design is the only way to create internal\ncommitment and self-organization in a team.* Interests, Not Positions is\nseemed to be an intractable standoff, with neither side willing to give up\ntheir positions: the oil company wanted to drill, and the farmers wanted to\nfarm.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 149, "segment_id": "00149"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 151, "segment_id": "00151"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["organization", "positions", "because", "harder", "design", "only", "interests", "company", "working", "means"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Mercy Corps", "oil company"], "people": ["Arthur Martirosyan"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "oil company", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["joint design", "employee motivation", "negotiation techniques"], "key_concepts": ["Joint Design", "Interests, Not Positions", "Combining Advocacy and Inquiry"], "problem_statement": "Creating internal commitment and self-organization in a team", "solution_approach": "Jointly designing the Why for the organization through negotiation and compromise", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00151", "page_num": 151, "segment": "However, Martirosyan detected an opportunity to refocus the\ndiscussion on each side’s interests: he observed that the oil wasn’t going\nanywhere, but the farmer’s harvest was near at hand.\n\nCould the oil company wait a short time to take over the land? Yes, as\ntheir interest was in protecting their claim and exploiting the resource for\nmany years to come.\n\nCould the farmers harvest and then leave? Yes, as their interest was in\n\nselling the crops they had worked hard to plant and to grow.\n\ne resolution was obvious as soon as the conversation shifted to\ninterests: the crops matured, the farmers harvested, and then the drills\nmoved in, right after the tractors left. Some of the farmers even got jobs on\nthe oil eld!\n\nDifficult conversations in your organization are unlikely to involve\nevicting tenants or dodging (literal) bullets, but your colleagues may have\npositions that are just as entrenched as those of the oil company and the\nfarmers, if not more so. It’s important to try to identify these positions\nahead of any difficult conversation, as well as some thoughts on possible\ncorresponding interests. (Don’t forget your own positions and interests!) As\nusual, enlisting the help of someone from outside the organization can\noften help you in identifying these, as you may be blind to them.\n\nTable 5.1 provides some examples of positions and their corresponding\n\ninterests.\n\nPosition\n\nPossible Corresponding Interests\n\nWe must release feature X this\n\nquarter.\n\nKeeping up with competitors\nDelivering on customer promises\nProtecting reputation for on-time\n\ndelivery\n\nWe must eliminate our technical\n\nDelivering quality products", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": true, "tables": [{"table_id": "table_1", "rows": 3, "cols": 2, "data": [["Position", "Possible Corresponding Interests"], ["We must release feature X this\nquarter.", "Keeping up with competitors\nDelivering on customer promises\nProtecting reputation for on-time\ndelivery"], ["We must eliminate our technical", "Delivering quality products"]], "markdown": "| Position | Possible Corresponding Interests |\n|---|---|\n| We must release feature X this\nquarter. | Keeping up with competitors\nDelivering on customer promises\nProtecting reputation for on-time\ndelivery |\n| We must eliminate our technical | Delivering quality products |"}], "table_count": 1, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Could the farmers harvest and then leave? Table 5.1 provides some examples of positions and their corresponding Possible Corresponding Interests", "l2_summary": "Could the oil company wait a short time to take over the land? Could the farmers harvest and then leave? Yes, as their interest was in Some of the farmers even got jobs on\nthe oil eld! Table 5.1 provides some examples of positions and their corresponding Possible Corresponding Interests", "prev_page": {"page_num": 150, "segment_id": "00150"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 152, "segment_id": "00152"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["interests", "farmers", "positions", "some", "corresponding", "harvest", "could", "company", "time", "interest"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Martirosyan"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["conflict resolution", "interest-based negotiation", "difficult conversations"], "key_concepts": ["positions and interests", "resolution through mutual benefit"], "problem_statement": "Conflict between oil company and farmers over land use", "solution_approach": "Identifying and focusing on the underlying interests of both parties to reach a mutually beneficial resolution", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
