{"segment_id": "00153", "page_num": 153, "segment": "For instance, two of three startup founders were arguing vigorously\nover what sales strategy to adopt---one passionately in favor of expanding\nwithin existing customers, the other just as rmly espousing opening\nadditional markets with new products. e third founder watched in silence\nfor a while, until we invited her to interject. At this point, she drew a chart\non the whiteboard that illustrated a new way of understanding the interests\nof the other two founders (see Table 5.2). By introducing the vertical axis,\nshe made it possible for all of us to see that there was a shared interest in\noffering a mix of options to existing and new customers, ranging from\nknown and loved features to totally new ones, born from research. e\ndebate shifted to the much more productive topic of what this mix was\ncurrently and what it should be.\n\nTable 5.2: Product Insights\n\nTo prepare for the Why Conversation specically, try to create a table\nlike Table 5.1, where the positions are specic team or organization goals\nthat you think colleagues may advocate, and the interests describe the\nbroader principles that may be behind their advocacy.\n\nCombining Advocacy and Inquiry", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "At this point, she drew a chart\non the whiteboard that illustrated a new way of understanding the interests\nof the other two founders (see Table 5.2). e\ndebate shifted to the much more productive topic of what this mix was\ncurrently and what it should be. Table 5.2: Product Insights", "l2_summary": "For instance, two of three startup founders were arguing vigorously\nover what sales strategy to adopt---one passionately in favor of expanding\nwithin existing customers, the other 