{"segment_id": "00154", "page_num": 154, "segment": "As we noted in Chapter 2, our natural tendency is toward unilateral control\nand vigorous advocacy; we believe that if we just tell others what our views\nare, they will be forced by logic and our brilliant rhetoric to agree with us\n(since we are right anyway). Argyris tells us that paying attention to our\nconversations will help us unlearn this habit,5 and methods like TDD for\nPeople and Interests, Not Positions lead us away from this one-sided\nadvocacy toward transparency and curiosity. We are not the only ones with\nthe truth; and asking genuine questions will help us understand how others\nsee the situation, allowing us to come up with new solutions together.\n\nBut there are dangers in tilting too far toward pure inquiry. Consider\nhow one of us approached a conversation with a colleague, Sergiusz, about\nhow to get user input on a new report. Because both Jeffrey and Sergiusz\ndid conversational analyses, we have access to the thoughts of both---a\nunique three-column conversational analysis. Sergiusz and Jeffrey wrote\ndown the conversation together, and thus, both of their thoughts were\nrecorded (Sergiusz’s is in the left-hand column and Jeffrey’s is in the righthand column). What was actually said appears in the middle column.\n\nSergiusz and Jeffrey’s Conversation\n\nNote: read the center column first.\n\nWhat Sergiusz\nthought and felt\n\nWhat Sergiusz\nand Jeffrey\nactually said\n\nWhat Jeffrey thought\nand felt\n\nI think we should have a\nfollow-up meeting with\nRob, but I don’t think it is\nuseful to pursue others.\n\nSergiusz: I think we should\nsend the analysis to Rob.\nHis comments will tell us\nwhether we’re building the\nright thing.\n\nI’m not sure about that. I think he’s\ngot a lot of interest in the topic, but\nhe’s just one stakeholder among\nmany.\n\nHmm, okay. Let’s see\n\nJeffrey: What makes you\n\nMaybe there’s something I don’t", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Sergiusz and Jeffrey’s Conversation What Sergiusz\nand Jeffrey\nactually said Jeffrey: What makes you", "l2_summary": "Sergiusz and Jeffrey’s Conversation What Sergiusz\nthought and felt What Sergiusz\nand Jeffrey\nactually said What Jeffrey thought\nand felt Sergiusz: I think we should\nsend the analysis to Rob. Jeffrey: What makes you", "prev_page": {"page_num": 153, "segment_id": "00153"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 155, "segment_id": "00155"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["sergiusz", "jeffrey", "what", "column", "will", "think", "toward", "others", "conversation", "both"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Argyris", "Sergiusz", "Jeffrey"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": ["TDD for People and Interests, Not Positions"], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["unilateral control", "advocacy", "transparency and curiosity", "conversational analysis"], "key_concepts": ["natural tendency towards unilateral control", "methods like TDD for People and Interests, Not Positions", "conversational analysis"], "problem_statement": "The problem of unilateral control and advocacy in communication.", "solution_approach": "Using methods such as TDD for People and Interests, Not Positions to move away from one-sided advocacy towards transparency and curiosity.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00155", "page_num": 155, "segment": "where this is going.\n\nsay that?\n\nknow. I wasn’t part of earlier\nmeetings with Rob’s team.\n\nI think he manages the\nusers who are going to\nread the report.\n\nSergiusz: Because I got\nthe impression that his\nteam runs similar reports,\nand he’ll know what they\nshould look like.\n\nThis is turning into a duel,\nnot a discussion. I don’t\nthink these are genuine\nquestions.\n\nJeffrey: Well, there are\nothers who are interested\ntoo. Who is the report\nfor?\n\nI don’t think he is a manager; just\nan interested and vocal user.\n\nI suspect there’s an executive above\nRob who makes the real decisions.\nI’m not sure you have enough\nunderstanding to start building. I’ll\ntest my understanding and make\nsure we are aligned on the customer\nand the goal first.\n\nI really don’t think this is\nthe issue we should be\ndiscussing. We just need\nto get feedback, not\nrelitigate the purpose of\nthe report.\n\nI don’t agree. But maybe\nif you score this point, we\ncan get on with deciding\nhow to get feedback.\n\nThis is really going off the\nrails. Why are you crossexamining me? Are you\ntrying to make me look\nbad? I wish I could escape\nto a meeting, or a root\ncanal or something.\n\nSerguisz: It’s for\noperational managers,\nthe ones keeping the\nsystem running smoothly.\n\nI’m confused and a bit concerned.\nWhat problem do you think they are\nsolving?\n\nJeffrey: Nope, it’s for the\nbusiness sponsor, the one\nwho controls the budget.\nWhat will she do as a\nresult of getting the\nreport? Why are we\nbuilding it in the first\nplace?\n\nSerguisz: I’m not sure. It\nmight not lead her to do\nanything differently.\n\nAre you just making stuff up? You\ndon’t seem to understand the\ncustomer need at all.\n\nShe’d do nothing differently? Why\nwould we build it then?? I think we\nare really misaligned here. This is a\ngreat chance to make sure we’re on\nthe same page. Good thing I can\nspend some more time with you on\nthis.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "I think he manages the\nusers who are going to\nread the report. I don’t\nthink these are genuine\nquestions. Who is the report\nfor?", "l2_summary": "I think he manages the\nusers who are going to\nread the report. I don’t\nthink these are genuine\nquestions. Who is the report\nfor? I don’t think he is a manager; just\nan interested and vocal user. I really don’t think this is\nthe issue we should be\ndiscussing. Serguisz: I’m not sure.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 154, "segment_id": "00154"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 156, "segment_id": "00156"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["think", "report", "sure", "going", "what", "just", "make", "really", "know", "team"], "content_type": "discussion", "domain": "management|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Sergiusz", "Jeffrey", "Rob"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["report development", "team alignment", "customer understanding"], "key_concepts": ["report purpose", "stakeholder roles", "alignment with business goals"], "problem_statement": "Misalignment in the team regarding the report's target audience and its purpose", "solution_approach": "Clarifying the customer need, ensuring alignment on the report's goal, and testing understanding", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00156", "page_num": 156, "segment": "As you can see, although Jeffrey thought he was working toward a\nmutual understanding of the situation by presenting a series of questions,\nSergiusz felt he was being “led down the garden path,” and became\nincreasingly concerned that Jeffrey had a hidden agenda. e conversation\nhad a completely unintended effect: instead of increasing mutual learning,\nit led to mistrust and fear for Sergiusz.\n\nWe call this the Perry Mason Trap. When we ask a series of questions\nwithout explaining our reasoning or stating our views behind these\nquestions, we run the risk that our conversation partner will think we are\n---like the twentieth-century TV lawyer---leading up to some unpleasant\nsurprise. (“Aha! So you admit you drive a bright pink sports car---just like\nthe one seen speeding away from the scene of the crime!”)\n\nTo avoid this trap, aim to combine advocacy of your own position with\ninquiry about that of your conversation partner, as espoused by Peter\nSenge in e Fifth Discipline: e Art & Practice of the Learning Organization.6\nis takes a lot of practice to do skillfully, so here are some example\napproaches to achieving this difficult combination:\n\n• “It seems to me that we have to cut the hiring budget to match\nthese reduced revenues. Do you see this differently? For example,\nare there any other areas we could look at cutting, or is making cuts\nthe wrong way to respond?”\n\n• “I wonder how many different ways we can offer this product. I’ve\nthought of two---on the home screen and as an add-on at checkout.\nWhat other ideas can you think of?”\n\n• “I hear some of our client implementations are behind schedule, and\nI’m wondering if we should delay some of them. You’re closer to the\ndelivery teams; how do you see the situation? And what solution\nwould you suggest?”", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "e conversation\nhad a completely unintended effect: instead of increasing mutual learning,\nit led to mistrust and fear for Sergiusz. Do you see this differently? What other ideas can you think of?”", "l2_summary": "As you can see, although Jeffrey thought he was working toward a\nmutual understanding of the situation by presenting a series of questions,\nSergiusz felt he was being “led down the garden path,” and became\nincreasingly concerned that Jeffrey had a hidden agenda. e conversation\nhad a completely unintended effect: instead of increasing mutual learning,\nit led to mistrust and fear for Sergiusz. Do you see this differently? What other ideas can you think of?” • “I hear some of our client implementations are behind schedule, and\nI’m wondering if we should delay some of them. You’re closer to the\ndelivery teams; how do you see the situation?", "prev_page": {"page_num": 155, "segment_id": "00155"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 157, "segment_id": "00157"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["some", "questions", "conversation", "jeffrey", "thought", "mutual", "situation", "series", "sergiusz", "learning"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Jeffrey", "Sergiusz"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Perry Mason Trap", "communication strategies", "mutual understanding"], "key_concepts": ["hidden agenda", "unintended effect", "mistrust and fear"], "problem_statement": "The problem of leading someone down the garden path through a series of questions without explaining the reasoning or views behind them.", "solution_approach": "Combining advocacy of one's own position with inquiry about that of the conversation partner.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00157", "page_num": 157, "segment": "A fortunate side effect of combining advocacy and inquiry is that you\nalso remind yourself to include your own observations and ideas in the\nconversation, sharing your Ladder of Inference---something that is\nsurprisingly easy to forget once you start aiming for greater mutual\nlearning. Once you’ve managed to be transparent about your own view and\ncurious about the other persons’ ideas, you are well on your way to mining\nmuch more value from your conicts.\n\nSoon after the invention of cake mix, one of its early manufacturers***\n\nnoticed a problem: many housewives**** refused to buy it. is is odd, its\nexecutives thought; why would anyone prefer the messy process of measuring\nand sifting and stirring when they could just add water to some powder from a\nbox?\n\nis had the company stumped for a while, until someone had the\nbright idea to actually ask some customers. ey discovered that the cake\nmix method was too easy---it didn’t feel like baking if there was only one\nstep to follow. Customers wanted to feel proud of making their family\nsomething sweet and delicious; but with the mix, they weren’t involved.\ney felt like they might as well have gone to the bakery and bought one of\nthe cakes off the shelf.9\n\ne solution was obvious: remove the powdered egg, and require the\ncustomer to break and stir in an honest-to-goodness real egg. e phrase\n“add your own egg” on the front of the box***** gave enough involvement\nand agency to the customer to make the process feel like real baking again,\nand sales shot up.******", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Soon after the invention of cake mix, one of its early manufacturers*** ey discovered that the cake\nmix method was too easy---it didn’t feel like baking if there was only one\nstep to follow. ey felt like they might as well have gone to the bakery and bought one of\nthe cakes off the shelf.9", "l2_summary": "Soon after the invention of cake mix, one of its early manufacturers*** ey discovered that the cake\nmix method was too easy---it didn’t feel like baking if there was only one\nstep to follow. Customers wanted to feel proud of making their family\nsomething sweet and delicious; but with the mix, they weren’t involved. ey felt like they might as well have gone to the bakery and bought one of\nthe cakes off the shelf.9 e solution was obvious: remove the powdered egg, and require the\ncustomer to break and stir in an honest-to-goodness real egg. e phrase\n“add your own egg” on the front of the box***** gave enough involvement\nand agency to the customer to make the process feel like real baking again,\nand sales shot up.******", "prev_page": {"page_num": 156, "segment_id": "00156"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 158, "segment_id": "00158"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["feel", "like", "ideas", "something", "easy", "once", "well", "cake", "process", "some"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["cake mix manufacturer"], "people": [], "products": ["cake mix"], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "cake mix manufacturer", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["advocacy and inquiry", "Ladder of Inference", "customer feedback"], "key_concepts": ["combining advocacy and inquiry", "sharing Ladder of Inference", "customer involvement in the process"], "problem_statement": "Many housewives refused to buy cake mix because it felt too easy and lacked the feeling of real baking.", "solution_approach": "Adding a step that required breaking and stirring an egg made the process feel more like real baking, increasing sales.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00158", "page_num": 158, "segment": "Baking a Better Decision\n\nWe often see teams trying to make decisions---about process, or\nestimation, or tooling, or budget, or even who sits where---in a centralized,\nnonconsultative way. Leaders pursuing efficiency and correctness make\nfundamental decisions and then communicate them to the team, expecting\nenthusiastic adoption of the new plan. All too often, as with the cake-mix\ncustomers, the reaction is decidedly less positive, with reluctant compliance\nat best or at refusal at worst. And of course, this is catastrophic when it\ninvolves the most fundamental decision of all: the denition of the team’s\nmotivating Why.\n\nInstead, for decisions big and small, use the process of Joint Design,\n\nwith each member of the team “adding their own egg.” Here is the process:\n\n• Include as many people as possible.\n• Ask genuine questions (see Chapter 2).\n• Invite opposing views.\n• Timebox the discussion.\n• Establish and communicate who will make the nal decision (known\n\nas a decision-making rule11).\n\nFirst, observe that the techniques of the previous section---Interests,\nNot Positions and Combining Advocacy and Inquiry---will be very useful in\nyour Joint Design discussion. When you ask genuine questions, listen for\nand inquire about the interests behind the answers you hear. And when you\ninvite opposing views, remember to also advocate appropriately. If you can\ndo this, even with only partial success, you will be helping everyone provide\nuseful information and feel like part of the decision.\n\nNotice a Joint-Design process doesn’t need to be the same as a\ndemocratic or consensus-driven one. e decision rule can mean that there\nis no need for everyone to agree with the decision, or even for most of the", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Baking a Better Decision • Establish and communicate who will make the nal decision (known as a decision-making rule11).", "l2_summary": "Baking a Better Decision And of course, this is catastrophic when it\ninvolves the most fundamental decision of all: the denition of the team’s\nmotivating Why. Instead, for decisions big and small, use the process of Joint Design, • Establish and communicate who will make the nal decision (known as a decision-making rule11). e decision rule can mean that there\nis no need for everyone to agree with the decision, or even for most of the", "prev_page": {"page_num": 157, "segment_id": "00157"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 159, "segment_id": "00159"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["decision", "process", "make", "decisions", "even", "team", "when", "joint", "design", "will"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Joint Design"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Decision Making", "Team Collaboration", "Joint Design Process"], "key_concepts": ["Centralized Decision-Making", "Nonconsultative Approach", "Reluctant Compliance", "Genuine Questions", "Opposing Views", "Timeboxing", "Decision-Making Rule"], "problem_statement": "Teams making decisions in a centralized, nonconsultative way leading to negative reactions and poor adoption.", "solution_approach": "Using the Joint Design process where team members contribute equally, asking genuine questions, inviting opposing views, timeboxing discussions, and establishing clear decision-making rules.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00159", "page_num": 159, "segment": "group to endorse it; and the timebox---the xed amount of time set for the\ndiscussion---ensures that we won’t get bogged down in endless debate. e\nkey elements are inclusion (“I was part of the decision, and my objections\nwere heard”) and information ow (“I was able to share what I know”). Over\nand over, we see that we make better decisions and earn meaningful\ninternal commitment when we follow this process.\n\nScoring for Joint Design\n\nTo score a Two-Column Conversational Analysis for Joint Design, look at\nthe ve elements listed above and award yourself a point for each one you\ncan observe in your discussion. Did you include everyone who was relevant\nand available? Did you pose genuine questions and encourage views that\ndon’t match yours? And was the conversation limited both by an agreed\ntime limit and by a decision-making rule? Scoring ve of ve means you\nsucceeded in making a decision that is likely to have everyone’s internal\ncommitment.\n\nJoint Design for Every Taste\n\nere are many avors of Joint Design. We’ve seen it used in groups of two\nand groups of two hundred, in short meetings and over many weeks, with\nsmall and large decisions. To illustrate just one variety, consider the fteenperson engineering team we worked with whose release process was error\nprone and slow. Everyone agreed some automation and discipline would\nhelp, and we had a pretty good idea what an improved process might look\nlike. It would have been easy to simply design a new deployment protocol\nand implement it.\n\nInstead, remembering the cake-mix lesson, we gathered the team\ntogether and drew the current process on a whiteboard, marking the areas", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Scoring for Joint Design Joint Design for Every Taste ere are many avors of Joint Design.", "l2_summary": "Over\nand over, we see that we make better decisions and earn meaningful\ninternal commitment when we follow this process. Scoring for Joint Design To score a Two-Column Conversational Analysis for Joint Design, look at\nthe ve elements listed above and award yourself a point for each one you\ncan observe in your discussion. Scoring ve of ve means you\nsucceeded in making a decision that is likely to have everyone’s internal\ncommitment. Joint Design for Every Taste ere are many avors of Joint Design.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 158, "segment_id": "00158"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 160, "segment_id": "00160"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["design", "process", "joint", "decision", "everyone", "time", "discussion", "elements", "what", "decisions"], "content_type": "tutorial", "domain": "devops|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": ["whiteboard"], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Agile", "DevOps"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["whiteboard"], "topics": ["Joint Design Process", "Decision Making", "Agile Methodology"], "key_concepts": ["Inclusion", "Information Flow", "Timeboxing", "Internal Commitment"], "problem_statement": "Improving decision-making and commitment in a team", "solution_approach": "Using the Joint Design process with clear elements like inclusion, information flow, timeboxing, and decision-making rules", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00160", "page_num": 160, "segment": "of friction and inefficiency in red. We set a timer and made this\nannouncement:\n\n“is is today’s release process, and here are the bits you’ve told us\naren’t working well. For the next twenty minutes, we’ll listen to any and all\nproposed changes; and using this eraser and pen, we’ll update the steps\naccordingly. When the timer goes off, we’re going to publish whatever is on\nthe board as our new release process and ask all of you to try it. If it’s a\ndisaster, we’ll buy everyone a beer in two weeks. Who wants to start?”\n\nIdeas ew in from all sides, including several we wouldn’t have thought\nof, making use of tools we didn’t know about and contextual information\nfrom several specialties like QA and system administration. Further, it\nturned out we hadn’t understood the existing process correctly, and we had\nto add a few steps to our diagram to make it work at all. In just a few\nminutes, we had a much better design on the board than we would have\ncome up with by ourselves---and everyone in the room felt like they were\npart of that design. ey enthusiastically implemented the new system---\nwhich was indeed smoother and less buggy than the old one---and we\ndidn’t have to buy anyone a beer.\n\nWe believe “adding your own egg” is vital to successfully determining\n\nyour team’s motivating Why. Now let’s see how that works.\n\nThe Conversation: Building a Why\n\nHow do organizations normally dene their purpose, decide their strategy,\nor start on a major transformation? In our experience, it’s typically a task\naddressed by a board of directors, a small group of leaders, or just a couple\nof executives. ey retreat in some way (to a boardroom or an off-site\nlocation), argue and debate and cogitate, and return to present a mission\nstatement or a roadmap or a values denition. en the rest of the\ncompany is expected to applaud politely and return to work.\n\nIf you’ve been paying attention to the last fe