{"segment_id": "00166", "page_num": 166, "segment": "Example Why Conversations\n\nTheresa and the Tech Team: Choosing a Focus\n\neresa says, “I’m the newly hired engineering leader for a team that’s\nfrankly been way off track for some time. e company needs them to start\ndelivering to business priorities, and I need their internal commitment to a\nnew direction.\n\n“I decided to call a Why Conversation meeting with developers and\n\nproduct managers to agree on and jointly design the way forward.”\n\nTheresa and the Tech Team’s Conversation\n\nWhat Theresa thought and\nfelt\n\nWhat Theresa and the team\nsaid\n\nI’ll lay out the ground rules to start: I need\ninformation flow from every-one, and a clear\ndecision at the end.\n\nTheresa: Thanks for coming, everyone. We’re\ngoing to spend the next hour setting our\nteam direction. I expect everyone to\nparticipate and propose ideas, but I may step\nin to make a decision if needed. At the end of\nthe hour, whatever is on this whiteboard will\nbe our direction for the next month. Everyone\ngot that?\n\nEngineers: Yes, we’ve got it.\n\nPMs: Okay.\n\nLet’s get the team involved from the start in\nsetting the topics.\n\nTheresa: Okay, working with the PMs, I’ve\nprepared these sticky notes describing\nvarious items we might work on. First, have a\nlook at all of them and tell me if any are not", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Theresa and the Tech Team: Choosing a Focus Theresa and the Tech Team’s Conversation What Theresa and the team\nsaid", "l2_summary": "Theresa and the Tech Team: Choosing a Focus Theresa and the Tech Team’s Conversation What Theresa thought and\nfelt What Theresa and the team\nsaid Theresa: Thanks for coming, everyone. We’re\ngoing to spend the next hour setting our\nteam direction.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 165, "segment_id": "00165"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 167, "segment_id": "00167"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["theresa", "team", "start", "direction", "everyone", "tech", "need", "conversation", "what", "decision"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Theresa"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Why Conversation", "Setting Team Direction"], "key_concepts": ["ground rules for meetings", "information flow", "joint decision-making"], "problem_statement": "A newly hired engineering leader needs to realign a tech team with business priorities.", "solution_approach": "Conducting a Why Conversation meeting where developers and product managers agree on the direction and jointly design the way forward.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00167", "page_num": 167, "segment": "worth even examining. And if any important\nones are missing, add your own sticky note.\n\nGood point. Glad he’s participating.\n\nPatrick: We forgot single sign-on.\n\nTheresa: Go ahead and add it. Any others?\n\nI agree, but I might be missing something,\nespecially since I’m new to the team.\n\nQuentin: Test automation is up there, but\nshouldn’t it be a routine part of coding, not a\nproject?\n\nAdvocacy and inquiry seem to be working here.\n\nTheresa: I tend to agree, but what do others\nthink? I see nods, so I’m removing it. Other\nthoughts?\n\nNice observation. Glad she’s engaging.\n\nRoberta: There are three usability changes\nthat are almost the same.\n\nLet’s move on to categorization.\n\nNo more than three areas with this small\nteam---that’s a limit that I want to set clearly.\nIt sure seems to me that we need usability\nimprovements to stop customer churn, but\nI’m genuinely interested in other ideas.\n\nTheresa: That’s a good observation. Let’s\ngroup them together under the heading\n“usability.” What other categories make\nsense?\n\n[Over the next few minutes, six categories\nemerge.].\n\nTheresa: I want to focus on just three of\nthese for the next month, given our limited\ncapacity. I see usability as vital but don’t\nhave a strong opinion about the other two.\nWhich three would you pick? I’m especially\ninterested to hear from you if you disagree\nwith me.\n\nSam: I’d take automation, onboarding\nimports, and pricing simplification. All three\nreduce costs for operations.\n\nRoberta: Why not usability?", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Theresa: Go ahead and add it. Theresa: I tend to agree, but what do others\nthink? Theresa: That’s a good observation.", "l2_summary": "Theresa: Go ahead and add it. Theresa: I tend to agree, but what do others\nthink? Roberta: There are three usability changes\nthat are almost the same. Theresa: That’s a good observation. I see usability as vital but don’t\nhave a strong opinion about the other two. Roberta: Why not usability?", "prev_page": {"page_num": 166, "segment_id": "00166"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 168, "segment_id": "00168"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["three", "usability", "theresa", "other", "missing", "good", "glad", "others", "agree", "especially"], "content_type": "practice", "domain": "management|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Patrick", "Theresa", "Quentin", "Roberta", "Sam"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": ["sticky notes"], "topics": ["project management", "team collaboration", "prioritization"], "key_concepts": ["usability improvements", "single sign-on", "test automation"], "problem_statement": "Determining the most important areas to focus on for a small team with limited capacity", "solution_approach": "Categorizing and prioritizing tasks based on team input", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00168", "page_num": 168, "segment": "Sam: Easy---no cost reduction.\n\nI’m curious here. Is there a strong reason for\nreducing cost that I don’t know about?\n\nTheresa: What do others think? Is cost our\ndriving consideration this month?\n\nThat’s how I see it; I wonder if anyone\ndisagrees?\n\nPatrick: I don’t think so. It’s important, sure,\nbut we need revenue more.\n\nHmm. We just raised a million dollars. I’m not\nsure this is right.\n\nSam: We always need to conserve cash. The\ncompany can’t run on fumes.\n\nTime to make a ruling and keep us on track.\n\nRoberta: The CEO said yesterday that we need\nto land prospects, and we all know prospects\nconvert when they aren’t frustrated by poor\nusability and too many clicks.\n\nTheresa: This is a good debate, and I’m glad\nwe are having it. I’m going to step in and say\n---sorry Sam!---that pure cost-reduction\ninitiatives like automation have to be out this\nmonth. [I removed the automation sticky\nnotes.] We’re after new sales first, and we’re\nwilling to put up with some uncomfortable\ncosts to get them.\n\nQuentin: What about imports? Those help\nconvert customers, and at the same time,\nthey make setup a lot smoother for\noperators.\n\nTheresa: Very good point! What do you think,\nSam?\n\neresa continued in this way throughout the hour; and though not\neveryone agreed at the end, they all understood the Why behind the\nchoices the group had made. All were willing to work toward the three focus\nareas left on the board and understood, even if they still disagreed, why the", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Sam: Easy---no cost reduction. Theresa: What do others think? What do you think,\nSam?", "l2_summary": "Sam: Easy---no cost reduction. Theresa: What do others t