{"segment_id": "00185", "page_num": 185, "segment": "shared meanings (the numerator) over the total number of important words\n(the denominator):\n\nWords with Confirmed and Shared Meanings\nImportant Words\n\n.\n\nA promise is a imsy thing, easily made and just as easily broken. A\ncommitment should be more than a promise---something you make with\nconviction and knowledge, and execute with creativity and skill. You will be\nable to make stronger, more condent commitments if you can do two things:\nkeep each commitment as small as possible, and use a framework that makes it\neasy to deliver your small commitments over and over. e Walking Skeleton\ntechnique gives you both of these advantages.\n\nAlistair Cockburn coined the phrase “Walking Skeleton” in the 1990s to\ndescribe a repeated pattern he observed in early iterative-delivery teams. As he\ntells it in Agile Software Development: e Cooperative Game, a project designer\ntold him this story:\n\nWe had a large project to do, consisting of systems passing\nmessages around a ring to each other. e other technical lead\nand I decided that we should, within the first week, connect the\nsystems together so they could pass a single null message\naround the ring. is way we at least had the ring working.\n\nWe then required that at the end of every week, no matter\nwhat new messages and message processing was developed\nduring the week, the ring had to be intact, passing all of the\nprevious weeks’ messages without failure. is way, we could", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Words with Confirmed and Shared Meanings\nImportant Words We had a large project to do, consisting of systems passing\nmessages around a ring to each other. is way we at least had the ring working.", "l2_summary": "shared meanings (the numerator) over the total number of important words\n(the denominator): Words with Confirmed and Shared Meanings\nImportant Words A promise is a imsy thing, easily made and just as easily broken. A\ncommitment should be more than a promise---something you make with\nconviction and knowledge, and execute with creativity and skill. We had a large project to do, consisting of systems passing\nmessages around a ring to each other. is way we at least had the ring working.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 184, "segment_id": "00184"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 186, "segment_id": "00186"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["ring", "words", "messages", "week", "shared", "meanings", "important", "promise", "easily", "commitment"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "programming|devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Alistair Cockburn"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": ["Walking Skeleton technique"], "methodologies": ["Agile"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Commitments", "Walking Skeleton technique", "Agile methodology"], "key_concepts": ["commitment", "walking skeleton", "small commitments", "framework for iterative delivery"], "problem_statement": "Making strong and reliable commitments in software development projects", "solution_approach": "Using the Walking Skeleton technique to ensure small, consistent progress", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00186", "page_num": 186, "segment": "grow the system in a controlled manner and keep the different\n\nteams in sync.5\n\nHere, the “ring” that bears the messages is the Walking Skeleton. Like a real\nskeleton, it gives the system a meaningful structure from which you can\ndiscern the nal intended form---you can look at a skeleton and immediately\ndistinguish, say, whether it belongs to a sh or a frog, even if you can’t tell\nexactly which species it is. And from just the above description of the ring\nsystem, you can determine quickly that it is going to involve some sort of\ninternetwork communication. But unlike a real skeleton, the ring system\n“walks” because it actually performs a function, passing messages, even if they\nare initially just trivial ones.\n\nAs a result of these two characteristics of the Walking Skeleton, its\nstructure and its function, it also provides a language for describing\ncommitments and a mechanism for their delivery: “By Friday I’ll have the\npayment message passing around the ring, though it may not be validated yet.”\nAnd it lets the team keep each change very small and immediately deliverable;\nyou can start with a null message, then gradually add content and additional\ntypes and routing, until you wind up with the nal system.\n\nIn modern software design, the Walking Skeleton may manifest as a clientside interface, often in a browser, talking to a very simple back-end system\nwith a database and appropriate integrations to third parties. For instance,\nLondon-based startup Unmade helps apparel companies offer customizable\nclothing using software that integrates with their retail and manufacturing\noperations. For a recent project, their Walking Skeleton had a stripped-down\nuser interface---little more than a couple of color pickers---and a basic output\nle sent to the garment manufacturer in a single format, with xed values for\nparameters like size and t. Despite its simplicity, this was enough to produce\nan 