lear communication and accountability among teams in a growing startup", "solution_approach": "Implementing the Accountability Conversation to clarify goals, discover options for achieving them, and radiate team intentions; fostering a Theory Y culture to create a healthy accountability environment", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00206", "page_num": 206, "segment": "Danny knew all too well that development doesn’t always go to plan.\nAnd in fact, he enjoyed the part of his job where developers came to him\nwith problems---he loved discussing technical options and working with\nproduct designers and the business to nd creative solutions. With many of\nthe older teams, this dynamic was still working well, and the developers did\ncome to him with problems; there were minor snags and bugs, to be sure,\nbut he didn’t fear a nasty surprise at the end of a sprint. However, some of\nthe newer teams were much more unpredictable, with major features\nslipping by weeks and sometimes months.\n\nDanny put his head in his hands and tried to come up with a plan.\nShould he introduce a daily progress report? Hire a delivery manager?\nReplace one of the team leads? He wasn’t sure what step to take next, but\nhe knew something had to change.\n\nDanny’s response is a common one. If we are being repeatedly,\nunpleasantly surprised---missed deadlines, system downtime, budget\nshortfalls---we want to take action to end those surprises. e normal\napproach is to ask for more detailed information, to provide more specic\ninstructions, or to put in more detailed controls. Or sometimes all three!\nUnfortunately, these instinctive responses often make things worse,\nbecause they miss the root of the problem: accountability.\n\nWhat do we mean by being accountable? We mean simply being\nobligated to render an account of what you have done and why. A feeling of\naccountability, held by each person, is one of the keys to success.\nAccountability is akin to ownership, to responsibility, and to agency. If I am\nin control of how I spend my time, then only I am able to provide the\ninformation on why I have done what I’ve done, providing the reasoning\nand the intent behind my actions.\n\nNotice that we are dening accountability very differently from most\npeople. When we hear a manager saying she will “hold someone\naccountable,” our instinct may be to duck under the nearest desk; the\nphrase connotes correction or punishment for doing something wrong.\n(See the sidebar on the next page for a historical perspective that may", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Danny’s response is a common one. e normal\napproach is to ask for more detailed information, to provide more specic\ninstructions, or to put in more detailed controls. What do we mean by being accountable?", "l2_summary": "Danny knew all too well that development doesn’t always go to plan. Danny put his head in his hands and tried to come up with a plan. He wasn’t sure what step to take next, but\nhe knew something had to change. Danny’s response is a common one. e normal\napproach is to ask for more detailed information, to provide more specic\ninstructions, or to put in more detailed controls. What do we mean by being accountable?", "prev_page": {"page_num": 205, "segment_id": "00205"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 207, "segment_id": "00207"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["more", "what", "accountability", "danny", "done", "knew", "well", "plan", "developers", "problems"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Danny"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Accountability in Development Teams", "Managing Unpredictable Teams", "Problem Identification and Resolution"], "key_concepts": ["accountability", "ownership", "responsibility", "agency"], "problem_statement": "Danny faces challenges with unpredictable newer teams and needs to find a solution.", "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00207", "page_num": 207, "segment": "explain this fear.) e person being held accountable is expected to feel\ncontrite, to learn from their mistakes. By contrast, our denition suggests\nthat you can be accountable for a success, a failure, or a neutral result. But\n“Let’s hold someone accountable for doubling sales last month!” is probably\nnot a sentence any of us hear very often.\n\nOur version of accountability---the obligation to explain our results---is\nkey to the self-organization that Agile, Lean, and DevOps teams aim for.\nEach team member is empowered to make their own decisions about how\nto allocate time and energy. However, with this empowerment comes an\nexpectation to share what those decisions are and why they were made.\nSometimes the Accountability Conversation takes the form of sharing\nintentions: “Here is what I’m planning to do and why.” Other times it is a\ndebrieng or a formal report on a past event. Whatever form this\naccountability takes, Danny will be able to scale his efforts more\nsuccessfully if he suppresses his instinct for control and, instead, builds a\nculture of accountability within his team.\n\nis probably sounds simple to do; and yet being effectively accountable\nis a learned skill. It requires, as usual, difficult emotional work, cultural\nchange, and much practice. In particular, an effective Accountability\nConversation requires high Trust (“I believe you will share my story about\nhow I performed”), low Fear (“I know you won’t overreact to my account of\nwhat I did”), an agreed Why (“We are headed for this vision, and here’s how\nfar we got today”), and a clear Commitment (“Here’s my account: I\ncommitted to do A and what actually happened was B”). You’re more likely\nto succeed if you and your team have had each of these conversations\nbefore embarking on the Accountability Conversation.\n\nS: M A", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "e