{"segment_id": "00213", "page_num": 213, "segment": "Most people have little creativity---\nexcept when it comes to getting\naround rules.\n\nCreativity and ingenuity are widely\ndistributed and grossly underused.\n\nNiels Paeging, “Why We Cannot Learn a Damn ing from Toyota, or Semco.\"\n\nTable 7.1: eory X and eory Y\n\nis is no surprise, of course; as we’ve looked at each of the previous\nfour conversations, we’ve seen story after story of software teams\nsucceeding through behaviors consistent with eory Y, like building trust,\nexplaining motivation rather than imposing a vision, and providing context\nto drive commitment. In fact, we agree with Niels Paeging that adoption\nof eory Y is a precondition for success with Agile, Lean, or DevOps\nmethods.9\n\nDrama or Leadership?\n\nSo what puzzles us is why eory X is still so pervasive in teams that are, at\nleast in theory, adopting people-centric software methods. Why would\nanyone retain a cultural schema that actively discourages accountability (in\nour sense)?\n\nWe’ll leave an exhaustive answer to the social scientists, but we suspect\na contributing factor may be the examples shown in television and movies,\nwhich supply our rst models of leadership. Some lms portray the strong,\ndecisive leader barking orders---someone who is rm but fair. Tough. Not\nafraid of calling out someone who is screwing up. e other trope is the\nineffective manager, Dilbert’s “pointy-haired boss,” who is always asking for\nstatus reports and nitpicking the details while missing the big picture.\nNeither of these approaches are examples of effective leadership, in part\nbecause they are at odds with true accountability (the decisive leader won’t", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Niels Paeging, 