{"segment_id": "00215", "page_num": 215, "segment": "Another obstacle standing in the way of the Accountability Conversation is\n\nnaïve realism.10 is is the view that we see the world objectively and\nwithout bias, and further, that other people will come to the same\nconclusions as we do, based on the same observations. When we adopt this\nsimplistic view of the world, we see less need to communicate and certainly\nsee no requirement to render an account; after all, everyone else observes\nthe same things we do, so why would we need to explain our actions or\ntheir results? Of course, this approach is misguided, and we need the\nAccountability Conversation precisely because others may have\ninformation we don’t possess; and they may draw different conclusions\nabout results than we do.\n\nere is a structured way to eliminate our bias toward naïve realism,\nand from a surprising source: the practices of the Prussian military in the\nnineteenth century. Stephen Bungay describes this method, which he calls\n“Directed Opportunism,” in his book e Art of Action: How Leaders Close the\n\nGaps between Plans, Actions and Results.11\n\nBungay begins with a description of “friction,” the sum of all those ways\nMurphy’s Law (“whatever can go wrong will go wrong”) does its work. e\nresults of friction are three gaps that arise in our attempt to convert the\noutcomes we desire into plans, our plans into actions, and those actions\ninto the outcomes we intended (see Figure 7.2 on page 164):\n\n• e knowledge gap is the difference between what we would like to\n\nknow and what we actually know.\n\n• e alignment gap is the difference between what we want people to\n\ndo and what they actually do.\n\n• e effects gap is the difference between what we expect our actions\n\nto achieve and what they actually achieve.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Gaps between Plans, Actions and Results.11 know and what we actually know. do and what they actually do.", "l2_summary": "Gaps between Plans, Actions and Results.11 • e knowledge gap is the difference between what we would like to know and what we actually know. do and what they actually do. • e effects gap is the difference between what we expect our actions to achieve and what they actually achieve.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 214, "segment_id": "00214"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 216, "segment_id": "00216"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": true, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["what", "actions", "results", "same", "need", "plans", "difference", "actually", "accountability", "conversation"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Stephen Bungay"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["Directed Opportunism"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["naïve realism", "Accountability Conversation", "Directed Opportunism"], "key_concepts": ["naïve realism", "knowledge gap", "alignment gap", "effects gap"], "problem_statement": "The obstacle of naïve realism in the Accountability Conversation", "solution_approach": "Using Directed Opportunism to address gaps caused by friction", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00216", "page_num": 216, "segment": "Figure 7.2: Bungay’s ree Gaps\n\nAdapted from “Executing Strategy: Some Propositions,” StephenBungay.com, accessed October 3, 2019,\nhttps:///ExecutingStrategy.\n\ne management-centric approach to the three gaps above is to try and\neliminate them. To close the knowledge gap, leaders seek more detailed\ninformation. To close the alignment gap, they give more specic\ninstructions. And to close the effects gap, they implement more detailed\ncontrols. Fully closing the gaps is impossible, however, and our increasingly\ndetermined attempts to do so cause suffering. In response to such\nauthoritarian micromanagement, “commitment is replaced by compliance,\nenergy is sapped, and morale declines.”12\n\nAs an alternative, Bungay offers his Directed Opportunism method,\nwhich he reverse engineered from the strategic and tactical innovations of", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Figure 7.2: Bungay’s ree Gaps To close the knowledge gap, leaders seek more detailed\ninformation. And to close the effects gap, they implement more detailed\ncontrols.", "l2_summary": "Figure 7.2: Bungay’s ree Gaps Adapted from “Executing Strategy: Some Propositions,” StephenBungay.com, accessed October 3, 2019,\nhttps:///ExecutingStrategy. e management-centric approach to the three gaps above is to try and\neliminate them. To close the knowledge gap, leaders seek more detailed\ninformation. To close the alignment gap, they give more specic\ninstructions. And to close the effects gap, they implement more detailed\ncontrols.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 215, "segment_id": "00215"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 217, "segment_id": "00217"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": true, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["gaps", "close", "more", "bungay", "detailed"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Stephen Bungay"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Three Gaps", "Knowledge Gap", "Alignment Gap", "Effects Gap", "Directed Opportunism"], "key_concepts": ["knowledge gap", "alignment gap", "effects gap", "authoritarian micromanagement", "commitment vs compliance", "energy sapped", "morale decline", "Directed Opportunism method"], "problem_statement": "Eliminating the three gaps in management", "solution_approach": "Closing the knowledge, alignment, and effects gaps through detailed information, specific instructions, and detailed controls; proposing Directed Opportunism as an alternative", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00217", "page_num": 217, "segment": "Prussian military leaders during their wars with France, Denmark, and\nAustria during the 1800s. e Prussians found that communicating plans\nand intentions clearly, both up and down the chain of command, was vital\nfor mastering the increasing complexity of nineteenth-century warfare.\nus the core of Directed Opportunism is a protocol between the parties:\none person uses a brieng to describe where we are going, and the other uses\na “back brieng” to explain how we plan to get there.\n\nAligning through a Briefing\n\nIn a brieng, one person communicates her intended outcome, provides\nconstraints within which that outcome should be sought, and describes\nfreedoms available during execution. For example, Bungay tells the story of\na commander who told two of his generals to move their divisions north to\nsurround the French (outcome) without being slowed down by engagement\nwith the enemy (constraint), and by using whatever route made the most\nsense for them (freedom).13*\n\nBy providing the desired outcome and its associated freedoms and\nconstraints, the person providing the outcome is being accountable. ey\nare providing information only they can provide, such as priorities and the\ntrade-offs they value. is is very different from the eory X approach,\nwith plans handed down from on high, where what the organization wants\nto achieve is, at best, intermixed with how things should be done; and there\nis little to no freedom to stray from the dictated path.\n\nBesides being wasteful of human resourcefulness, this approach of\nplanning from the top often falls into the knowledge gap, where the\nmanagers doing the planning lack the knowledge and experience of those\ncloser to where the work is done. How could the Prussian commander\npossibly know the right route for his subordinates to choose from miles\naway, and without the benet of modern battleeld information sources,", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "us the core of Directed Opportunism is a protocol between the parties:\none person uses a brieng to describe where we are going, and the other uses\na “back brieng” to explain how we plan to get there. In a brieng, one person communicates her intended outcome, provides\nconstraints within which that...", "l2_summary": "Prussian military leaders during their wars with France, Denmark, and\nAustria during the 1800s. us the core of Directed Opportunism is a protocol between the parties:\none person uses a brieng to describe where we are going, and the other uses\na “back brieng” to explain how we plan to get there. In a brieng, one person communicates her intended outcome, provides\nconstraints within which that outcome should be sought, and describes\nfreedoms available during execution. For example, Bungay tells the story of\na commander who told two of his generals to move their divisions north to\nsurround the French (outcome) without being slowed down by engagement\nwith the enemy (constraint), and by using whatever route made the most\nsense for them (freedom).13* By providing the desired outcome and its associated freedoms and\nconstraints, the person providing the outcome is being accountable. ey\nare...", "prev_page": {"page_num": 216, "segment_id": "00216"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 218, "segment_id": "00218"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["outcome", "where", "down", "person", "brieng", "providing", "prussian", "plans", "uses", "there"], "content_type": "theory|practice", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Bungay"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Prussian military strategy", "briefing protocol", "communication in command"], "key_concepts": ["Directed Opportunism", "outcome, constraints, freedoms"], "problem_statement": "Communicating plans and intentions clearly within the chain of command", "solution_approach": "Using a briefing to describe outcomes, constraints, and freedoms", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00218", "page_num": 218, "segment": "like drones and radios? Far better to equip them with clear intent and allow\nthem to make the right choice based on the local data that only they have.\n\nA good example of a clear brieng was provided by Boeing during the\ndesign phase of their 777 airliner.14 Designers were struggling with\nlowering the overall weight of the airplane while also keeping the cost\nwithin the planned budget. How could they get the best trade-offs between\nweight savings and cost savings in the design for the whole craft? Should\nthey, for example, use a more expensive rudder to save weight while\nchanging to more efficient but heavier landing gear? With hundreds of\nengineers working in separate groups on a large number of subsystems, it\nwas very difficult to see where it was even possible to make such a swap of\ncost for weight on widely separated, unrelated parts of the airplane.\n\ne solution Boeing found was to provide a brieng to engineers about\nwhat trade-offs they could and should make on their local subsystem in the\nform of simple cost guidelines. An engineer could spend up to $300 to save\na pound without approval; spending up to $600 per pound needed only a\nlocal supervisor’s okay; and even more, up to $2,500, could be spent to save\na pound if a program manager gave the go-ahead. ese guidelines claried\nthe constraints within which the engineers needed to work, providing a\nframework that allowed them to make decisions while ensuring that those\ndecisions were aligned with the overall goal of minimizing cost and weight.\n\nCementing Agreement with a Back Briefing\n\nIf we stopped the Directed Opportunism protocol with just a clear brieng,\nwe would already have a great improvement, with at least one party\nproviding accountability. However, even with a detailed brieng, it is easy\nfor misunderstandings, both large and small, to arise. To account for and\ndetect these imperfections, we also schedule a response to the brieng: a\n“back brieng” led by the executing party, which is meant to describe how it\nplans to achieve the desired outcome and to conrm that this plan matches", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "A good example of a clear brieng was provided by Boeing during the\ndesign phase of their 777 airliner.14 Designers were struggling with\nlowering the overall weight of the airplane while also keeping the cost\nwithin the planned budget. How could they get the best trade-offs between\nweight savings...", "l2_summary": "Far better to equip them with clear intent and allow\nthem to make the right choice based on the local data that only they have. A good example of a clear brieng was provided by Boeing during the\ndesign phase of their 777 airliner.14 Designers were struggling with\nlowering the overall weight of the airplane while also keeping the cost\nwithin the planned budget. How could they get the best trade-offs between\nweight savings and cost savings in the design for the whole craft? Should\nthey, for example, use a more expensive rudder to save weight while\nchanging to more efficient but heavier landing gear? e solution Boeing found was to provide a brieng to engineers about\nwhat trade-offs they could and should make on their local subsystem in the\nform of simple cost guidelines. An engineer could spend up to $300 to save\na pound without approval; spending up to $600 per pound needed only a\nlocal...", "prev_page": {"page_num": 217, "segment_id": "00217"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 219, "segment_id": "00219"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["brieng", "weight", "cost", "make", "could", "clear", "local", "while", "more", "save"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Boeing"], "people": [], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "Boeing", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["clear briefing", "trade-offs between weight and cost", "back briefing"], "key_concepts": ["Directed Opportunism protocol", "local data-driven decision making", "cost guidelines"], "problem_statement": "How to achieve optimal trade-offs between weight savings and cost savings in the design of a large aircraft like the Boeing 777?", "solution_approach": "Providing clear cost guidelines to engineers to make local decisions while ensuring alignment with overall goals.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00219", "page_num": 219, "segment": "the original outcome, constraints, and freedoms. is accounting for what\npeople plan to do and why they plan to do it---this sharing of reasoning and\nintent---ensures that there is alignment across all parties.\n\nIn e Art of Action, Bungay shows us the letter written by von Moltke,\nthe chief of the Prussian General Staff, the commander mentioned earlier,\nwho wanted two of his armies to pursue and surround the French. His\nletter describes the situation, his intention, the role of each general, and\nspecial directions in case the French crossed into Belgium. e letter\nnishes by providing a deadline for the generals to inform him of the\ninstructions they would be issuing to their armies.15 e generals’\nresponses were back briengs, which allowed von Moltke to coordinate the\nmovement of his own army with that of his subordinates, and to correct\nany misinterpretations.\n\nWith one of our own clients, a children’s retailer, we set up a system of\nback briengs in which the COO would review product plans with the\nleadership of each team. Before one of these sessions, we could see how\nexcited the product manager was to share the plans for the revised ecommerce shop through which parents would be able to purchase from a\nwidely expanded range of products. During the meeting, however, the COO\nlooked less and less pleased as the product manager showed screenshots\nand early prototypes of the new pages. Eventually he said, “But where do\nwe explain the benets?” It turned out that in focusing on supporting new\nproduct types and exciting new ways to buy them, the team had forgotten\nthat the site had to sell the products as fun and educational, something the\nmarketing group was relying on it to do. It was painful to revise the plans\nbut much better to have caught the problem early, before much code had\nbeen written. Clearly, the combination of brieng and back brieng is a\npowerful method for creating mutual accountability.\n\nScoring for Briefings and Back Briefings", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "e letter\nnishes by providing a deadline for the generals to inform him of the\ninstructions they would be issuing to their armies.15 e generals’\nresponses were back briengs, which allowed von Moltke to coordinate the\nmovement of his own army with that of his subordinates, and to correct\nany...", "l2_summary": "His\nletter describes the situation, his intention, the role of each general, and\nspecial directions in case the French crossed into Belgium. e letter\nnishes by providing a deadline for the generals to inform him of the\ninstructions they would be issuing to their armies.15 e generals’\nresponses were back briengs, which allowed von Moltke to coordinate the\nmovement of his own army with that of his subordinates, and to correct\nany misinterpretations. With one of our own clients, a children’s retailer, we set up a system of\nback briengs in which the COO would review product plans with the\nleadership of each team. During the meeting, however, the COO\nlooked less and less pleased as the product manager showed screenshots\nand early prototypes of the new pages. It was painful to revise the plans\nbut much better to have caught the problem early, before much code had\nbeen written. Scoring for...", "prev_page": {"page_num": 218, "segment_id": "00218"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 220, "segment_id": "00220"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["back", "product", "letter", "would", "which", "plans", "plan", "written", "moltke", "general"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["children’s retailer"], "people": ["von Moltke", "COO", "product manager"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "children’s retailer", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["back briefings", "alignment across parties", "sharing reasoning and intent"], "key_concepts": ["back briefings", "mutual accountability", "aligning plans and intentions"], "problem_statement": "Forgetting to align the product's marketing goals with its functional features", "solution_approach": "Implementing a system of back briefings to ensure all parties are aligned on both the 'what' and 'why' of their actions", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00220", "page_num": 220, "segment": "You can score a conversation as a brieng if it involves making a request.\nDisplay your score as a fraction over three, providing yourself one point for\neach of the three elements: intended outcome, constraints within which\nthat outcome should be sought, and freedoms available during execution. If\nyou provided some constraints or some freedoms but not all, give yourself\npartial credit, such as 0.5 if you described half the constraints. For example,\nif you shared your intended outcome and all the constraints but did not\n\ndescribe any freedoms, you score would be\n\n2\n3\n\n.\n\nSimilarly, you can score a conversation as a back brieng if you are\nresponding to a request. As with the brieng, display your score as a fraction\nover three and give yourself one point for including each of three elements:\nyour intended action, your reasoning for adopting that action, and your\nconrmation that your plans match the brieng provided by the other\nperson.\n\nThe Conversation: Radiating Intent\n\nSay you’re planning to drive to a holiday destination with your family. How\ndo you decide who needs what information and when to share it?\nCollaborating on a road trip is very similar to interacting with your team\nusing the Accountability Conversation.\n\ne start of the journey is straightforward, but before we embark, we\nneed to have a shared understanding of the information required for\nplanning---the brieng. is includes the intended outcome (“We’re going\nto the lake house via Sacramento, where we’re picking up your sister”) as\nwell as the constraints (“Avoid highway 5; too much traffic”) and available\nfreedoms (“We can stop at your favorite restaurant”). Once this is clear, we\nshould then return with the equivalent of the back brieng: the intended\nroute, the reasoning for proposing that route, and a request for\nconrmation that the intended route seems satisfactory. But what happens\nonce the trip starts?", "sour