y_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Accountability Conversation", "Radiating Intent"], "key_concepts": ["constant course corrections", "emergency response", "transparency of intentions"], "problem_statement": "Effective communication and accountability in a team or project", "solution_approach": "Maintaining transparency with intentions, contributing to the Accountability Conversation", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00222", "page_num": 222, "segment": "We’ve spoken to two companies so far, neither of whom have\nproducts that meet our standards.”\n\n• Describe plans and intended outcomes: “We are seeing three more\nvendors next week, and also exploring an in-house solution. We\nshould have a workable solution by the end of the month.”\n\n• Alert to obstacles: “It’s possible that the budget reforecast will mean\n\nwe have to drop this project entirely. We’ll know by ursday.”\n\nWith an appropriate eory Y mind-set, and by using the mutual\nlearning tools you’ve been practicing in previous chapters, you should nd\nthat the Accountability Conversation is informative and valuable for\nkeeping your project on track. But be wary---the Accountability\nConversation is not a once-and-done affair.\n\nTrusting and Verifying\n\n“He trusts, but he doesn’t verify,” said the head of Engineering at one of our\nclients, describing the CEO. (e familiar phase “Trust but verify” was\nRonald Reagan’s famous dictum, derived from a Russian proverb, about\nnegotiating nuclear treaties with the Soviet Union.17) “He gave us the\nvision and the focus for our team,” she continued, “but without regular\ninteraction, we weren’t able to stay aligned. We pursued a version of the\nmission that was awed; and when he ew in from headquarters to see us,\nhe said we had to scrap three months of work and start over.”\n\nWe nd that one of the most difficult things about the Accountability\nConversation isn’t having the discussion itself but remembering to continue\nhaving it. Like our client’s CEO, you may think that you’re done once you’ve\nagreed on the direction for a project---especially if you’ve used a brieng\nand a back brieng to double-check for alignment on the desired outcome,\nthe freedoms, and the constraints. After all, won’t the other party resent", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "We\nshould have a workable solution by the end of the month.” we have to drop this project entirely. But be wary---the Accountability\nConversation is not a once-and-done affair.", "l2_summary": "We’ve spoken to two companies so far, neither of whom have\nproducts that meet our standards.” We\nshould have a workable solution by the end of the month.” we have to drop this project entirely. But be wary---the Accountability\nConversation is not a once-and-done affair. “He trusts, but he doesn’t verify,” said the head of Engineering at one of our\nclients, describing the CEO. We nd that one of the most difficult things about the Accountability\nConversation isn’t having the discussion itself but remembering to continue\nhaving it.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 221, "segment_id": "00221"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 223, "segment_id": "00223"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["have", "project", "accountability", "conversation", "three", "solution", "should", "once", "done", "verify"], "content_type": "theory|practice", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["head of Engineering", "CEO"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Accountability Conversation", "Trust and Verification"], "key_concepts": ["mutual learning tools", "Theory Y mindset", "project tracking"], "problem_statement": "Finding a suitable product or solution for a project within budget constraints", "solution_approach": "Exploring multiple vendors, in-house solutions, and maintaining regular communication", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00223", "page_num": 223, "segment": "our intrusion? Doesn’t eory Y say we should trust others’ good\nintentions and leave them alone to get on with the task?\n\nese are valid objections, as micromanagement is to be avoided\nwhenever possible (we don’t want someone in the back seat telling us how\nto steer the car); but neither party to the Accountability Conversation\nshould be disengaging lest disastrous misalignment strikes. e briefer\nneeds to hear how execution is progressing, because they have an\nobligation to check alignment and the responsibility to coordinate their\nown actions. In addition, the briefed party needs feedback on their\nprogress as well as updates on how the external situation is changing,\nespecially if that affects the work to be done. e frequency of check-ins\nwill vary with the importance of the project and its level of risk, but “set it\nand forget it” is not the philosophy we suggest when it comes to the\nAccountability Conversation.\n\nUsing Agile Radiators\n\nLuckily, modern software development methods come with ceremonies and\nprocesses that are perfect for triggering the\ninitial Accountability\nConversation and providing regular opportunities to radiate intent and\nprogress.\n\nPlanning. Scrum, XP, and similar methodologies give us a natural\ntime for discussing accountability: the sprint planning session. Lean\nor Kanban teams have more frequent, pull-triggered planning\nactivities but still need to break down tasks and agree on acceptance\ncriteria, often during or just after the daily standup. During your\nteam’s planning activity, ensure you include time to discuss all three\nelements of the Accountability Conversation: current state,\nintended outcomes, and potential obstacles. Going beyond the usual\nroadmapping and estimation activities to include more context will", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table"