akeholders.", "solution_approach": "Focusing on deliverables that are visible to non-technical stakeholders, conducting effective accountability conversations, and sharing progress through demonstrations and videos.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00226", "page_num": 226, "segment": "tend to default to accepting a confident “got it” when, in fact, it might be wiser\nto ask more questions.\n\nScoring the briefing, I don’t think I included any of the elements fully. Being\nreally charitable, maybe my explanation of the dierences from the current\nreport communicated half of the desired outcome. But I definitely didn’t\nmention freedoms (the developers would have been welcome to order the\ncolumns in any convenient way, for example) or constraints (the report has to\nbe in a native Excel format, not tab- or column-separated). So at best, a 0.5\nout of three here.\n\nI’d like to get better by asking more questions rather than jumping to the\nconclusion that everything is okay. I think it will help to be more structured in\nmy approach to briefings and back briefings, because that will prompt me to be\nmore curious about what I’m saying and hearing. Finally, I’m going to try sharing\nmore of my reactions rather than trying to look confident all the time. I hope\nthis will help me work with Bobby and others more eectively, and avoid\nunpleasant surprises.\n\nImproved Conversation\n\nI checked with Bobby last week on the progress of the development team he\nworks with. I wanted to handle this back briefing better, in line with what I\nlearned from the earlier conversation. I asked a trusted friend to Role Play this\ndiscussion ahead of time, and that helped me be more curious as I went into the\nconversation.\n\nNicole and Bobby’s Improved Conversation\n\nWhat Nicole thought and felt\n\nWhat Nicole and Bobby said\n\nI wonder what he’s prioritizing.\n\nNicole: You’ve got a lot of different projects", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Improved Conversation Nicole and Bobby’s Improved Conversation What Nicole and Bobby said", "l2_summary": "I think it will help to be more structured in\nmy approach to briefings and back briefings, because that will prompt me to be\nmore curious about what I’m saying and hearing. I hope\nthis will help me work with Bobby and others more eectively, and avoid\nunpleasant surprises. Improved Conversation Nicole and Bobby’s Improved Conversation What Nicole thought and felt What Nicole and Bobby said", "prev_page": {"page_num": 225, "segment_id": "00225"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 227, "segment_id": "00227"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["more", "what", "bobby", "conversation", "nicole", "will", "confident", "questions", "briefing", "think"], "content_type": "practice", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Bobby", "Nicole"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["briefing effectiveness", "questioning approach", "communication improvement"], "key_concepts": ["asking more questions", "structured briefing approach", "sharing reactions"], "problem_statement": "Improving the effectiveness of briefings and back briefings", "solution_approach": "Implementing a structured questioning approach and sharing personal reactions", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00227", "page_num": 227, "segment": "in flight. Where do you plan to focus this\nweek?\n\nHe’s made a lot more progress than I realized.\nUm, wait---that’s my twitch firing. I should\ncheck this out further.\n\nBobby: I’m thinking we’re ready to finish the\nwork on simplified configuration. I think I can\nget that done by Friday.\n\nWe haven’t discussed how he’d present the\nfindings from this investigation.\n\nNicole: Great! So how do you plan to present\nthe results?\n\nWhat?! It sounds like he’s already moved on\nto implementation, and I haven’t even seen\nthe proposal yet.\n\nMaybe he published his analysis and I missed\nit?\n\nOh dear! I thought I had been clear.\n\nI don’t want to be making arbitrary decisions.\n\nThis sounds more like what I was expecting to\nhear.\n\nBobby: Last week I reviewed all the current\nconfig options, and the team has removed\nmost of them. I expect I’ll be able to\ndemonstrate the new page with just five or six\noptions.\n\nNicole: Wait a minute---I’m confused. I was\nexpecting you to examine and explain the need\nfor each option, and I don’t remember seeing\na review document from you. Have you already\ndone the analysis and moved onto\nimplementation?\n\nBobby: What? I thought you wanted me to get\nrid of as many options as possible. We\ndecided that Monday, when we said we’d\nsimplify the config.\n\nNicole: No, not really. What I wanted was to\nget your opinion on each option. Which of\nthem do customers actually need and use?\n\nBobby: Oh! Okay, well, that changes my plans\nfor the week. We can pause the changes to\nthe page, and I can focus on talking to more\ncustomers. We won’t have the new page ready\nthis week, though.\n\nI’m glad we had this conversation---we dodged\na bullet here. We might have released the new\n\nNicole: That’s not a problem. It will be good to\nhave greater confidence in our decision to", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Where do you plan to focus this\nweek? Nicole: No, not really. Nicole: That’s not a problem.", "l2_summary": "Where do you plan to focus this\nweek? This sounds more like what I was expecting to\nhear. Nicole: No, not really. What I wanted was to\nget your opinion on each option. We won’t have the new page ready\nthis week, though. Nicole: That’s not a problem.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 226, "segment_id": "00226"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 228, "segment_id": "00228"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["week", "bobby", "nicole", "what", "have", "more", "options", "page", "plan", "focus"], "content_type": "practice", "domain": "management|architecture", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["He", "Bobby", "Nicole"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Project Management", "Configuration Simplification"], "key_concepts": ["Progress Tracking", "Decision Making", "Team Communication"], "problem_statement": "Misalignment in project progress and decision-making between team members", "solution_approach": "Clarifying expectations, revisiting goals, and ensuring clear communication", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00228", "page_num": 228, "segment": "page prematurely if we hadn’t checked in.\n\nkeep, drop, or change the options, whichever\nwe decide on.\n\nHaving this conversation really helped both Bobby and me. Sharing the plan\nof action uncovered a gap in alignment: we both came into the conversation\nthinking we had a shared understanding of what “simplified configuration”\nmeant, but we were actually far apart.\n\nPreviously I would have just assumed we agreed on this and accepted\nBobby’s assertion that the work would be done Friday. Instead, I asked Bobby\nfor an account of what he planned to deliver and shared my emotions when I\nheard that he was planning something very dierent\n\nAs a result, our misalignment was in the open, and we could fix it before it\ndid much damage. I still have some doubts about Bobby’s listening skills, but I\ncan see now that I was contributing to the problem. I think I can work with him\nmuch better in the future by using the Accountability Conversation.\n\nExample Accountability Conversations\n\nGrace and Lisa: Finding a Better Solution\n\nGrace says, “From talking with our clients, we know that end-user\nengagement is important to them. We came up with a good solution to the\nproblem, namely emailing a reminder at the start of the week to inactive\nusers. We were almost ready to roll out the weekly reminders, and so we\nscheduled brieng calls with our key accounts to let them know what was\ncoming. Most of them were very happy with our proposal, but one client,\nLisa, had a very different reaction.”\n\nGrace and Lisa’s Conversation", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Having this conversation really helped both Bobby and me. Grace and Lisa: Finding a Better Solution Grace and Lisa’s Conversation", "l2_summary": "Having this conversation really helped both Bobby and me. I still have some doubts about Bobby’s listening skills, but I\ncan see now that I was contributing to the problem. I think I can work with him\nmuch better in the future by using the Accountability Conversation. Grace and Lisa: Finding a Better Solution Most of them were very happy with our proposal, but one client,\nLisa, had a very different reaction.” Grace and Lisa’s Conversation", "prev_page": {"page_num": 227, "segment_id": "00227"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 229, "segment_id": "00229"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversation", "bobby", "what", "very", "grace", "lisa", "both", "came", "shared", "would"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Bobby", "Grace", "Lisa"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Accountability Conversation", "Misalignment in Understanding", "Effective Communication"], "key_concepts": ["shared understanding", "misalignment", "accountability conversation"], "problem_statement": "Misunderstanding of 'simplified configuration' between team members", "solution_approach": "Having an accountability conversation to uncover and address misalignments", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00229", "page_num": 229, "segment": "What Grace thought and felt\n\nWhat Grace and Lisa said\n\nI know Lisa has been concerned about\nengagement for a while. I expect she’ll be\nhappy with this, so I’ll just explain what we’re\ndoing and why.\n\nGrace: Hi Lisa, thanks for taking the time to\nhear about a change we are planning to\nimplement. We are going to start sending an\nemail on Mondays to any users who didn’t log\nin the previous week. We are doing this in\nresponse to clients who are worried that endusers aren’t always as engaged with the\nsystem as they’d like.\n\nWhat?! You’ve complained to me about\nengagement again and again. I thought you’d\nbe grateful.\n\nLisa: Ugh, please don’t do that!\n\nWeird, no other customer has objected to the\nemails. I’m pretty sure engagement is still a\nproblem for you, but I should check.\n\nWow, sounds awful. No wonder she doesn’t\nwant us emailing users directly. And I’m glad\nshe has an idea about what might work for\nthem instead.\n\nThis could be a good experiment. If it works, it\nmight be something we can offer to other\nclients.\n\nMe too!\n\nGrace: Oh, that’s surprising! I’ve spoken with\nseveral other clients, and you are the first\nperson with that reaction. Looking at the\nlatest usage report, I can see that 40% of\nyour users are inactive. Do you see that as a\nproblem?\n\nLisa: Engagement is definitely something we\nwant to improve. It’s just that we already get\nso many emails sent from internal systems\nthat it is impossible to keep up; and the last\nthing I want are complaints about getting\neven more. Could you send me a weekly report\non inactive users instead? That would allow us\nto follow up internally.\n\nGrace: Absolutely. I can tell our team that\nyou’d rather receive the information on\ninactive users instead of emailing the users\ndirectly. In our next quarterly review, we can\ntalk about how those reports are working and\nif there’s anything else we can do in the\nsystem to help.\n\nLisa: That’s great. I’m really glad you\ncontacted me ahead of time rather than", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "What Grace thought and felt What Grace and Lisa said Grace: Oh, that’s surprising!", "l2_summary": "What Grace thought and felt What Grace and Lisa said I know Lisa has been concerned about\nengagement for a while. Grace: Oh, that’s surprising! Looking at the\nlatest usage report, I can see that 40% of\nyour users are inactive. Lisa: Engagement is definitely something we\nwant to improve.", "prev_page": {"page_num": 228, "segment_id": "00228"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 230, "segment_id": "00230"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["lisa", "users", "what", "grace", "engagement", "clients", "other", "want", "instead", "inactive"], "content_type": "practice", "domain": "management", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Grace", "Lisa"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": true, "has_metrics": true, "metrics": ["engagement", "user activity"], "has_case_study": false, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["User Engagement", "Email Campaigns", "Internal Communication"], "key_concepts": ["User Inactivity", "Engagement Improvement Strategies", "Client Feedback"], "problem_statement": "Improving user engagement and addressing client concerns about inactivity", "solution_approach": "Implementing an email campaign to remind inactive users, adjusting communication methods based on client feedback", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00230", "page_num": 230, "segment": "unleashing a flood of emails onto our users!\n\nIt is easy to believe that we understand both the problem and the\nsolution when, in fact, we lack a key piece of knowledge. Grace had a\nsolution that had been endorsed by several others for a problem she knew\nLisa cared about; she couldn’t have known that emails were an\nunacceptable approach in Lisa’s organization. Being accountable means\nsignaling our intent with others who will be impacted even when we think\nwe are right. ese opportunities come up most naturally inside the teams\nwe work with daily. It is also worth looking for opportunities across\ndepartments and even across companies.\n\nAndy and Wayne:\nUnderstanding Adaptation in the Moment\n\nAndy says, “At the nancial services company where I’m the Head of\nEngineering, when we perform an incident postmortem investigation, we\nare trying to understand not just what happened but also how the world\nlooked to the people involved at the time. Our goal is to reconstruct a\npicture where the actions taken were the right ones; because no matter\nwhat we learn after the fact, we trust that the actions must have seemed\nright at the time. And whatever we do to make our systems resilient, it is\nthe judgement and actions of the people in the moment that help us cope\nwith the unexpected. Like when we recently lost data for one of our\nproduction systems and I asked Wayne, one of our system administrators,\nto account for his actions in restoring service.”\n\nAndy and Wayne’s Conversation\n\nWhat Andy thought and felt\n\nWhat Andy and Wayne said", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Andy and Wayne:\nUnderstanding Adaptation in the Moment Andy and Wayne’s Conversation What Andy and Wayne said", "l2_summary": "It is easy to believe that we understand both the problem and the\nsolution when, in fact, we lack a key piece of knowledge. Being accountable means\nsignaling our intent with others who will be impacted even when we think\nwe are right. Andy and Wayne:\nUnderstanding Adaptation in the Moment Andy and Wayne’s Conversation What Andy thought and felt What Andy and Wayne said", "prev_page": {"page_num": 229, "segment_id": "00229"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 231, "segment_id": "00231"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["andy", "when", "wayne", "what", "actions", "right", "emails", "understand", "problem", "solution"], "content_type": "theory", "domain": "management|devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["nancial services company"], "people": ["Grace", "Lisa", "Andy", "Wayne"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "nancial services company", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["communication", "accountability", "incident postmortem"], "key_concepts": ["unacceptable approach", "signal intent", "reconstruct picture", "judgement and actions in the moment"], "problem_statement": "Unacceptable use of emails as a solution", "solution_approach": "Understanding adaptation in the moment through incident postmortems", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00231", "page_num": 231, "segment": "We have a normal process for restoring data.\nWhy didn’t they just use that?\n\nThat’s a good point. I’m sure we never expect\nthis kind of partial failure.\n\nAndy: Okay, that table was deleted and the\nservice was offline. Why was it that you didn’t\nuse the normal documented backup\nprocedure?\n\nWayne: Well, that process assumes the entire\ndatabase has been lost or corrupted. In our\nsituation it was only one table, and as a\nresult, most of the services were still\noperating normally. If we’d performed the\nnormal disaster recovery process, it would\nhave worked; but it also would have meant all\nthe services would be offline for a day or\nmore.\n\nIt must have been very stressful to realize\nnone of the processes we’d practiced would\napply.\n\nAndy: I see, so you were in uncharted territory\nhere.\n\nI agree---that would have made the problem\nmuch worse.\n\nI’m not sure I would have taken their\napproach, but they got their priorities right.\n\nWayne: That’s right! Of course we could have\njust followed the book, but that would have\nmade things worse. It didn’t seem like the\nright thing to do even though it was the\ndocumented process.\n\nAndy: So how did you figure out how to\nproceed?\n\nWayne: Our first goal was to keep all the\nother services operating normally, and our\nsecond goal was to recover the lost table and\nrestore the service that depends on it. We\nthought of multiple options for recovering\nthe data, and not knowing which would be\nfastest, we started down several of those\npaths in parallel, with different people\nworking on each one.\n\nI’m glad Wayne was thinking creatively here.\nPlaying it by the book would have meant hours\n\nAndy: That was sharp thinking! We should\nconsider adding “try multiple solutions” to", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "We have a normal process for restoring data. I agree---that would have made the problem\nmuch worse. Playing it by the book would have meant hours", "l2_summary": "We have a normal process for restoring data. If we’d performed the\nnormal disaster recovery process, it would\nhave worked; but it also would have meant all\nthe services would be offline for a day or\nmore. I agree---that would have made the problem\nmuch worse. I’m not sure I would have taken their\napproach, but they got their priorities right. Of course we could have\njust followed the book, but that would have\nmade things worse. Playing it by the book would have meant hours", "prev_page": {"page_num": 230, "segment_id": "00230"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 232, "segment_id": "00232"}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["have", "would", "process", "andy", "wayne", "normal", "didn", "table", "services", "right"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": [], "people": ["Andy", "Wayne"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": [], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": true, "has_antipatterns": true, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": null, "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["Data Recovery", "Disaster Recovery Process", "Problem Solving"], "key_concepts": ["Partial Failure", "Uncharted Territory", "Creative Problem Solving"], "problem_statement": "A partial failure occurred in a database, and the normal backup procedure did not apply.", "solution_approach": "The team decided to keep other services operating normally while attempting multiple recovery options simultaneously.", "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00232", "page_num": 232, "segment": "of downtime and a much bigger headache.\n\nthe runbook.\n\nIt is inevitable that things won’t always go according to plan, so how\nwill people respond when that happens? In Andy’s organization, the\nmessage is that you are expected to use your professional judgement in the\nmoment; and at the same time, you’ll be expected to account for your\nreasoning after the fact. e goal is not to punish people for the\nunexpected; it is to learn as much as possible from the experience. is\nfrees people to improvise and create better outcomes than a by-the-book\nmind-set would produce.\n\n“I got it!” exclaimed Mike, bursting through the office door with a huge\nbinder. “I got it! We’re back in!”\n\nMarcus, a product manager for London-based startup Arachnys, looked\nup skeptically. Mike had gone to see a major banking prospect to nd out\nwhy they had said no to the company’s anti-money-laundering product a\nfew weeks before. Marcus had expected Mike to return with a list of\nreasons the competitor had won, grist for the product-development mill to\nhelp them win the next bid with someone else. What had Mike cooked up\ninstead?\n\nMike excitedly spread out the contents of the binder. “ese are the\nspecications the bank gave the other guys. Apparently, after they got the\ndeal, the other company took one look at these and said they wouldn’t\ncommit to anything less than nine months for completion of the rst\nversion of the system, meeting all of these requirements. at’s way too", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "“I got it!” exclaimed Mike, bursting through the office door with a huge\nbinder. What had Mike cooked up\ninstead? Mike excitedly spread out the contents of the binder.", "l2_summary":