{"segment_id": "00245", "page_num": 245, "segment": "• “To the Rescue” by Roger Martin from the Stanford Social Innovation\n\nReview (https://ssir.org/articles/entry/to_the_rescue)\n\n• “Skilled Incompetence” by Chris Argyris from the Harvard Business\n\nReview (https://hbr.org/1986/09/skilled-incompetence)\n\nBooks\n\nDifficult Conversations by Bruce Patton, Douglas Stone, and Sheila\nHeen is a gentle introduction to the techniques we describe in Agile\nConversations.\n\ne Skilled Facilitator by Roger Schwarz and Discussing the\nUndiscussable by Bill Noonan are more advanced guides to\nconversational analysis, covering many applications and including\nreal-world examples.\n\ne Elephant in the Room by Diana McLain Smith and e\nResponsibility Virus by Roger Martin cover specic applications of\nconversational techniques to complex business relationships, such\nas those burdened with a long history of poor interaction or with\nconfusion over roles and responsibilities.\n\nAction Science by Chris Argyris, Robert Putnam, and Diana McLain\nSmith is the seminal work on the Action Science methods that\nprovided the bedrock for this book and several of the other\nresources in this list. It is more academic and theoretical than other\nwritings cited here, and has the additional virtue of being freely\navailable online.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "• “To the Rescue” by Roger Martin from the Stanford Social Innovation • “Skilled Incompetence” by Chris Argyris from the Harvard Business Review (https://hbr.org/1986/09/skilled-incompetence)", "l2_summary": "• “To the Rescue” by Roger Martin from the Stanford Social Innovation Review (https://ssir.org/articles/entry/to_the_rescue) • “Skilled Incompetence” by Chris Argyris from the Harvard Bus