{"segment_id": "00261", "page_num": 261, "segment": "T his book is built on a foundation formed of many conversations---some\n\njoyful, some painful, and all sources of learning. Here are some of the\npeople whose conversations with us have helped us grow and learn so far,\nand for whom we are very grateful:\n\nBenjamin Mitchell, who introduced us to the work of Chris Argryis, and\npatiently worked with us as we learned conversational analysis and much\nmore. Waseem Taj, Andy Parker, Jamie Mill, and Lisa Miller, who joined us\nin learning how to analyze conversations and to lose our fear of difficult\ninteractions. Rich Koppel and Colin Berthoud, the founders of TIM Group,\nand the many employees there who worked with us (especially with\nJeffrey), to experiment with growing a learning organization based on\ntransparency and curiosity. Steve Freeman, who encouraged us to tell the\nstory of the changes at TIM Group (this book doesn’t tell that story, but it\ndoes share the conversations behind those changes).", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "T his book is built on a foundation formed of many conversations---some joyful, some painful, and all sources of learning. Here are some of the\npeople whose conversations with us have helped us grow and learn so far,\nand for whom we are very grateful:", "l2_summary": "T his book is built on a foundation formed of many conversations---some joyful, some painful, and all sources of learning. Here are some of the\npeople whose conversations with us have helped us grow and learn so far,\nand for whom we are very grateful: Benjamin Mitchell, who introduced us to the work of Chris Argryis, and\npatiently worked with us as we learned conversational analysis and much\nmore. Waseem Taj, Andy Parker, Jamie Mill, and Lisa Miller, who joined us\nin learning how to analyze conversations and to lose our fear of difficult\ninteractions. Steve Freeman, who encouraged us to tell the\nstory of the changes at TIM Group (this book doesn’t tell that story, but it\ndoes share the conversations behind those changes).", "prev_page": {"page_num": 260, "segment_id": "00260"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 262, "segment_id": "00262"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["conversations", "some", "learning", "book", "many", "worked", "group", "tell", "story", "changes"], "content_type": "case_study", "domain": "management|other", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["TIM Group"], "people": ["Benjamin Mitchell", "Waseem Taj", "Andy Parker", "Jamie Mill", "Lisa Miller", "Rich Koppel", "Colin Berthoud", "Jeffrey"], "products": [], "technologies": [], "frameworks": [], "methodologies": ["transparency and curiosity"], "programming_languages": [], "has_best_practices": false, "has_antipatterns": false, "has_instructions": false, "has_metrics": false, "metrics": [], "has_case_study": true, "case_study_company": "TIM Group", "tools_mentioned": [], "topics": ["conversational analysis", "learning organization", "difficult interactions"], "key_concepts": ["transparency", "curiosity", "conversational learning"], "problem_statement": null, "solution_approach": null, "extraction_method": "lm"}}
{"segment_id": "00262", "page_num": 262, "segment": "e participants in our CTO Mentoring Circles and the London\nOrganisational Learning Meetup, which served as testbeds for many of the\nconcepts herein.\n\nChris Argyris and Donald Schön, whose theories underpin so much of\nthis book. Also those who developed their ideas, including Philip McArthur,\nRobert Putnam, and Diana McLain Smith of Action Design, and Roger\nSchwarz, whose Eight Behaviors helped us greatly\nin our early\nconversations.\n\nPatrick Lencioni, whose model of hierarchical dysfunctions informed\nthe order of our conversations. Amy Edmondson, who brought\n“psychological safety” to our vocabulary. Simon Sinek, who explained the\nvalue of Why. Stephen Bungay, who showed the value of brieng and back\nbrieng. Brené Brown, who helped us to put the story we were telling\nourselves into words. Dr. David Burns, who helped us understand the\nfractal nature of conversations---that we create our interpersonal reality.\n\nAlistair Cockburn, Kent Beck, and others of the early Agile software\ndevelopment community who pioneered the radical idea that relationships\nmatter, back when both of us were still trapped in the software factory.\nMary Poppendieck, Tom Poppendieck, Eric Ries, and others who helped\nbring Lean thinking to the software world. Patrick Debois, John Allspaw,\nand Paul Hammond, who helped shatter the silo that remained at the last\nmile, and who ensured that DevOps was about culture and not just tools.\n\nGeckoboard (including Paul Joyce and Leo Cassarani), Unmade Ltd.,\nand Arachnys, each of whom kindly allowed us to include the details of\ntheir work with us.\n\nAnna Shipman, whose insightful blog post became a case study.\nSofar Sounds, who kindly allowed us to include a story about them.\nSergiusz Bleja, who allowed us to include a case study we created with\n\nhim.\n\ne Belgian Federal Pensions Service, ierry de Pauw, and Tom Jans,\nwho kindly allowed us to include details from one of their projects as a case\nstudy.", "source_file": "Agile_Conversations_-_Douglas_SquirrelJeffrey_Fredrick.pdf", "extraction_method": "pdfminer", "ocr_used": false, "has_table": false, "chapter_num": "5", "chapter_title": "e Why Conversation", "section_num": null, "section_title": null, "l1_summary": "Simon Sinek, who explained the\nvalue of Why. Sofar Sounds, who kindly allowed us to include a story about them. Sergiusz Bleja, who allowed us to include a case study we created with", "l2_summary": "Amy Edmondson, who brought\n“psychological safety” to our vocabulary. Simon Sinek, who explained the\nvalue of Why. Stephen Bungay, who showed the value of brieng and back\nbrieng. Brené Brown, who helped us to put the story we were telling\nourselves into words. Sofar Sounds, who kindly allowed us to include a story about them. Sergiusz Bleja, who allowed us to include a case study we created with", "prev_page": {"page_num": 261, "segment_id": "00261"}, "next_page": {"page_num": 263, "segment_id": "00263"}, "flags": {"continuity_gap": true}, "extended_fields": {"has_code": false, "has_formulas": false, "has_diagram": false, "has_list": false, "has_citations": false, "key_terms": ["helped", "whose", "allowed", "include", "conversations", "software", "kindly", "case", "study", "including"], "content_type": "reference", "domain": "management|devops", "complexity": "intermediate", "companies": ["Geckoboard", "Unmade Ltd.", "Arachnys", "Sofar Sounds"], "people": ["Chris Argyris", "Donald Schön", "Philip McArthur", "Robert Putnam", "Diana McLain Smith", "Roger Schwarz", "Patrick Lencioni", "Amy Edmondson", "Simon Sinek", "Stephen Bungay", "Brené Brown", "Alistair Cockburn", "Kent Beck", "Mary Poppendieck", "Tom Poppendieck", "Eric Ries", "Patrick Debois", "John Allspaw", "Paul Hammond", "Anna Shipman", "Sergiusz Bleja", "Tierry de Pauw", "Tom Jans"], "products": [], "technologies": ["software factory"], "frameworks": ["Agile", "DevOps"], "methodologies": [], "programming_language